SECTION 3. FINDINGS.
================================================================================

Congress finds the following:

--- Constitutional Basis ---

(1) The Eighth Amendment to the Constitution of the United States prohibits the
infliction of cruel and unusual punishment, establishing that the severity of
any penal response must bear a proportional relationship to the harm addressed,
and that no system of punishment may operate in a manner inconsistent with the
evolving standards of decency that mark the progress of a maturing society.

(2) The Thirteenth Amendment to the Constitution abolishes involuntary
servitude except as punishment for crime, a clause whose historical application
to prison labor has perpetuated a system of coerced work that concentrates
economic benefit in private contractors and governmental entities at the expense
of incarcerated persons and their communities.

(3) The Fourteenth Amendment guarantees to all persons equal protection under
the law. The documented racial, economic, and geographic disparities in the
application of criminal law -- including disparities in arrest rates, charging
decisions, plea bargain outcomes, sentencing lengths, and conditions of
confinement -- constitute a systemic denial of equal protection that no
legitimate system of law may sustain.

(4) The Fifth Amendment prohibits the taking of property without due process of
law and without just compensation. The system of monetary assessments imposed
in connection with criminal proceedings -- including fines, fees, surcharges,
and civil asset forfeiture -- has, in application, operated as a mechanism for
extracting wealth from persons who have not been convicted of any offense and
from communities that can least afford such extraction, without any relationship
to the repair of harm.

(5) The First Amendment guarantees the freedom of association and the freedom
of conscience. Systems of mass incarceration that separate persons from their
families and communities for extended periods impose burdens on associational
freedom that, when imposed without proportional justification, cannot be
sustained under a constitution committed to human dignity.

--- The Failure of Punitive Incarceration ---

(6) The United States incarcerates more people per capita than any other nation
on earth. As of the date of enactment of this Act, approximately two million
persons are held in federal, state, and local correctional facilities, and
approximately five million additional persons are under probation or parole
supervision, for a total supervised population exceeding the combined population
of the twenty smallest states.

(7) The empirical evidence accumulated over decades of criminological research
demonstrates that incarceration, as currently practiced, does not reduce
recidivism. Persons released from incarceration reoffend at rates substantially
higher than comparable populations who receive community-based intervention,
restorative processes, or no intervention at all. The deterrent effect of
incarceration on potential offenders is marginal and significantly weaker than
the deterrent effect of swift, certain, and community-grounded accountability.

(8) The financial cost of incarceration to federal, state, and local
governments exceeds eighty billion dollars annually. This expenditure generates
no measurable net reduction in harm, produces substantial economic and social
harm to incarcerated persons and their communities, and diverts resources from
the material and social investments -- housing, nutrition, healthcare, education,
and meaningful work -- that empirical evidence identifies as the primary drivers
of genuine community safety.

(9) The communities most affected by incarceration are also the communities most
affected by disinvestment. Mass incarceration has operated, in practice, as a
mechanism for removing persons from communities already facing the structural
conditions that generate harmful behavior -- poverty, housing insecurity, food
insecurity, unemployment, and the absence of meaningful social participation --
rather than addressing those conditions. Removing individuals from communities
in crisis deepens the crisis, concentrating harm in the individuals removed and
the families and communities left behind.

(10) Private entities currently profit from the incarceration of human beings
through contracts for the operation of correctional facilities, the provision of
services to incarcerated persons at above-market rates, and the employment of
incarcerated labor at below-subsistence compensation. This profit motive creates
institutional incentives for the perpetuation and expansion of incarceration
that are irreconcilable with the goal of a justice system oriented toward the
reduction of harm.

--- The Evidence for Transformative Justice ---

(11) Transformative justice approaches -- including restorative circles, harm
repair agreements, community accountability processes, and the sustained
provision of material security as an alternative to punitive response -- have
demonstrated in domestic and international practice that communities can address
harm effectively, repair relationships between those who have caused harm and
those who have experienced it, and reintegrate participants into community life
at substantially lower rates of subsequent harm than punitive alternatives.

(12) The empirical research of Nobel laureate Elinor Ostrom demonstrated that
communities are capable of governing themselves and resolving conflicts
sustainably, provided that governance structures meet defined design principles
including collective decision-making, effective monitoring, accessible conflict
resolution, and recognized community autonomy. These principles, codified as
the Ostrom Standards of Stewardship under the Federal Resilience and
Decentralization Initiatives Act, provide the governance architecture for the
community safety institutions established by this Act.

(13) Nations and jurisdictions that have invested in material security -- stable
housing, adequate nutrition, accessible healthcare, meaningful employment, and
genuine social participation -- as the primary response to community harm have
achieved substantially lower rates of harmful behavior than jurisdictions
oriented primarily toward punitive response. The causal relationship between
material deprivation and harmful behavior is among the most robustly established
findings in social science.

(14) Indigenous communities throughout the United States and internationally
have maintained traditions of restorative and transformative justice that
predate the punitive system and that have demonstrated sustained effectiveness
in addressing harm, repairing relationships, and maintaining community
cohesion. These traditions represent a body of governance knowledge that the
transformative justice architecture established by this Act draws upon and
honors, without imposing uniformity upon communities whose own traditions may
differ.

--- The Systemic Causes of Harm ---

(15) The harmful behaviors that the justice system addresses are substantially
products of the material and social conditions in which those behaviors occur.
Housing insecurity, food insecurity, untreated mental health conditions,
substance use disorders, economic exclusion, and the experience of historical
and ongoing injustice do not excuse individual responsibility for harmful
conduct, but they establish that any justice system oriented toward the genuine
reduction of harm must address those conditions rather than responding only to
their behavioral expressions.

(16) The Guaranteed Provision Standard established under the Federal Resilience
and Decentralization Initiatives Act -- providing every Commons Member with
permanent housing, adequate nutrition, accessible healthcare, connectivity, and
access to the knowledge commons -- constitutes the most powerful available
intervention against the material conditions that generate harmful behavior.
The transformative justice framework established by this Act is inseparable from
and dependent upon the material security infrastructure established by that Act.

(17) Mental health conditions and substance use disorders, when untreated or
inadequately treated, contribute substantially to the behaviors that bring
persons into contact with the justice system. The treatment of these conditions
as criminal matters rather than health matters has produced decades of
demonstrably counterproductive outcomes. This Act establishes a framework for
addressing these conditions as health matters, through the cooperative healthcare
commons, while maintaining community accountability for harmful conduct through
restorative rather than punitive processes.

--- Reparative Justice and Historical Harm ---

(18) Communities that have been the systematic victims of governmental policies
producing demonstrable material harm -- including the forced displacement of
indigenous peoples, the enslavement of African Americans and the subsequent
century of economic exclusion enforced through law, the internment of Japanese
Americans, and the systematic underdevelopment of communities of color through
racially discriminatory housing, lending, and criminal enforcement policies --
are owed reparative recognition that the punitive justice system has not only
failed to provide but has, in many cases, deepened and extended.

(19) The reparative framework established by this Act addresses historical
institutional harm through mechanisms that are structurally different from
individual criminal accountability. Reparative Debt owed to communities is
discharged through the transfer of productive capacity and governance rights,
through the commons credit settlement architecture established in conjunction
with the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act, and through
the community-governed reparative justice proceedings of the Accountability
Coordination DAO established under Title II of this Act.

--- This Act Does Not Create a New System ---

(20) The restorative and transformative justice institutions that this Act
recognizes, connects, and capitalizes already exist and already function
throughout the United States and internationally. Community accountability
circles, restorative conferencing programs, community land trusts serving
formerly incarcerated persons, peer support and reentry cooperative enterprises,
and community health networks serving justice-involved populations represent an
existing institutional infrastructure whose demonstrated effectiveness justifies
the investment and legal architecture this Act provides. Law Enforcement
Assisted Diversion (LEAD) programs operating in Seattle, Washington; Santa Fe,
New Mexico; Albany, New York; and dozens of other municipalities have
demonstrated that pre-arrest diversion to community-based services, rather than
prosecution, substantially reduces recidivism and system contact for individuals
whose conduct stems from poverty, mental health conditions, or substance use.
Community mediation programs operating through many state court systems provide
existing practitioner infrastructure for the Community Mediation Network
established under Title IV of this Act. The Bay Area Transformative Justice
Collective and comparable organizations operating in cities throughout the
country have developed community accountability practices that do not rely on
the police or carceral systems, providing practitioner knowledge and tested
protocols that inform the Accountability Pod framework of Title II of this Act.
Peacemaking circles maintained within many tribal justice systems represent
traditional practices of restorative accountability that predate and in many
cases exceed in demonstrated effectiveness the practices developed by the
mainstream restorative justice movement, and whose principles inform this Act's
entire architecture. LabGov's Co-City Protocol and its implementation in Bologna
and more than 200 other cities demonstrate that commons-based community
governance can address safety, maintenance, and conflict resolution in urban
spaces through collaborative civic institutions rather than punitive enforcement,
providing a parallel international track of municipal commons governance
experience directly relevant to the Resilience Campus and Peace Keeper
architecture of Titles I and III of this Act. The experience of Portugal's 2001
drug decriminalization policy, which redirected drug-related enforcement
resources to health and social services and produced sustained reductions in
drug-related harms, overdose deaths, and incarceration rates, provides the
primary comparative policy precedent for the substance use decriminalization
provisions of Title IV of this Act. This Act removes the legal barriers,
provides the material infrastructure, and supplies the financial capitalization
necessary for these existing institutions to function at the scale the crisis
of mass incarceration demands.


