TITLE I -- DECARCERATION AND FACILITY TRANSFORMATION
================================================================================

The purpose of this Title is to establish the schedule, process, and governance
architecture by which the federal carceral system is wound down and its physical
infrastructure is converted to commons resilience use. The decommissioning of
federal correctional facilities is not an act of abandonment. It is an act of
reinvestment: the physical assets of a system that has consumed vast public
resources without producing safety are redirected to the construction of the
material commons that constitutes the genuine foundation of safe community life.
Every conversion authorized by this Title is governed by the communities that
will inhabit the resulting infrastructure, under the Ostrom Standards of
Stewardship, ensuring that the transition from carceral to commons serves those
most harmed by the prior system. No provision of this Title shall be operative
with respect to any facility unless the Qualified Federated Network that will
govern the resulting Resilience Campus has achieved certification pursuant to
Title I of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act, or has
been granted provisional certification through the expedited pathway of Section
103(e) of that Act, prior to the transfer of title.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 101. THE FEDERAL CORRECTIONAL DECOMMISSIONING SCHEDULE.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) MANDATORY DECOMMISSIONING.-- The Director of the Federal Bureau of Prisons
shall decommission all federal correctional facilities on a schedule established
by this Section. Decommissioning means the complete cessation of correctional
operations at the facility, the transfer of all persons in federal custody at
the facility to alternative placement pursuant to the provisions of this Title,
and the preparation of the facility for conversion pursuant to Section 102 of
this Title. Decommissioning does not mean demolition. The physical
infrastructure of every decommissioned facility shall be preserved for commons
conversion except where the Office of Federated Stewardship, in consultation
with the Tri-Partite Council constituted for the facility pursuant to Section
102(b) of this Title, determines that specific structures are unsuitable for
conversion due to environmental contamination, structural deficiency, or
documented community opposition.

(b) DECOMMISSIONING SCHEDULE.-- Federal correctional facilities shall be
decommissioned on the following schedule, with prioritization within each tier
determined by the criteria of subsection (c) of this Section:

    (1) TIER 1 -- WITHIN 24 MONTHS OF ENACTMENT.-- All federal correctional
    facilities that, as of the date of enactment of this Act:

        (A) hold a population consisting of fifty percent or more of persons
        whose controlling offense is a non-violent offense under federal law,
        defined as any offense not involving the threatened or actual use of
        physical force against a person;

        (B) hold a population consisting of fifty percent or more of persons
        who have served more than two-thirds of their imposed sentence;

        (C) have been designated by the Department of Justice as failing to meet
        minimum standards for humane conditions of confinement in any inspection
        conducted within the preceding five years; or

        (D) are privately operated under contract with the Bureau of Prisons or
        any other federal agency, consistent with the policy established under
        subsection (f) of this Section.

    (2) TIER 2 -- WITHIN 48 MONTHS OF ENACTMENT.-- All federal correctional
    facilities not decommissioned under Tier 1 that hold a population consisting
    primarily of persons whose sentences, under the Second Look resentencing
    process established in Section 104 of this Title, would be substantially
    reduced or whose release would be authorized.

    (3) TIER 3 -- WITHIN 60 MONTHS OF ENACTMENT.-- All remaining federal
    correctional facilities not decommissioned under Tiers 1 or 2, except for
    such facilities as are designated High-Security Retention Facilities pursuant
    to subsection (d) of this Section.

(c) PRIORITIZATION CRITERIA WITHIN TIERS.-- Within each tier, the Director of
the Federal Bureau of Prisons shall prioritize decommissioning in the following
order:

    (1) facilities located in or adjacent to communities designated as
    Underserved Areas or Priority Underserved Areas pursuant to Section 105(b)
    of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act, where
    conversion would provide the greatest marginal benefit to the surrounding
    community;

    (2) facilities located in communities where a Qualified Federated Network or
    proto-QFN organization has expressed readiness to assume governance of the
    converted facility;

    (3) facilities with the highest ratio of non-violent to violent offense
    populations; and

    (4) facilities with the longest documented history of conditions-of-
    confinement violations.

(d) HIGH-SECURITY RETENTION FACILITIES.-- A federal correctional facility may
be designated as a High-Security Retention Facility, exempted from the
decommissioning schedule of subsection (b) of this Section, only upon a specific
written finding by the Attorney General that:

    (1) the facility holds a population a significant portion of which consists
    of persons who have been convicted of offenses involving documented use of
    serious physical force against other persons, and for whom no community-based
    placement consistent with community safety is currently available;

    (2) the facility cannot be substituted by any combination of community-based
    placement, Resilience Campus residential programming, and supervised
    transition; and

    (3) the continued operation of the facility is the minimum necessary response
    to a genuine and documented safety need that the transformative justice
    framework established by this Act cannot yet address.

    High-Security Retention Facility designations shall be reviewed annually by
    the Attorney General and shall be presumptively revoked when the number of
    persons for whom no community-based placement is available falls below fifty
    percent of the facility's operational capacity. The total number of
    High-Security Retention Facility designations shall not exceed ten at any
    time during the first five years following enactment, and shall not exceed
    five at any time thereafter. The Attorney General shall report to Congress
    annually on the status of each designation and the progress toward its
    eventual revocation.

(e) DECOMMISSIONING PROCESS.-- The decommissioning of each facility shall
proceed through the following stages:

    (1) COMMUNITY NOTIFICATION.-- Not less than one year before the scheduled
    decommissioning date of a facility, the Bureau of Prisons shall provide
    written notice of the intended decommissioning to:

        (A) all persons currently in custody at the facility and their families
        or designated next-of-kin;

        (B) the governments of all counties, municipalities, and tribal
        jurisdictions within fifty miles of the facility;

        (C) the Office of Federated Stewardship, which shall immediately initiate
        the Tri-Partite Council formation process of Section 102(b) of this
        Title; and

        (D) any existing Qualified Federated Network or proto-QFN organization
        whose geographic boundaries include or are adjacent to the facility.

    (2) TRANSFER OF PERSONS IN CUSTODY.-- Prior to decommissioning, all persons
    in federal custody at the facility shall be transferred to one of the
    following placements, in order of preference:

        (A) release to Federated Commons Membership, with immediate access to
        the Guaranteed Provision Standard, pursuant to Section 103 of this Title,
        for any person who is eligible for release under the Second Look process
        of Section 104 of this Title or whose sentence has been fully served;

        (B) Resilience Campus residential placement at a converted facility
        within the same regional federation, for any person who has entered a
        Harm Repair Agreement pursuant to Title II of this Act and is completing
        the community service component;

        (C) transfer to a High-Security Retention Facility, for any person for
        whom the Attorney General makes the specific written finding required by
        subsection (d) of this Section; or

        (D) in no case shall any person in federal custody be transferred to a
        state or local facility under conditions that are less protective of their
        rights than the conditions established by this Act, and in no case shall
        any person be held in a facility scheduled for decommissioning beyond the
        facility's decommissioning date.

    (3) ENVIRONMENTAL ASSESSMENT.-- Prior to title transfer, the Bureau of
    Prisons shall conduct a comprehensive environmental assessment of the
    facility, with remediation of any identified contamination completed at
    federal expense prior to or concurrent with title transfer, on terms
    equivalent to those established for surplus military land under Section 905
    of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act.

    (4) TITLE TRANSFER.-- Upon completion of the environmental assessment and the
    transfer or release of all persons in custody, title to the facility and all
    associated land shall transfer to the Qualified Federated Cooperative
    constituted as the Tri-Partite Council's designated receiving entity pursuant
    to Section 102(c) of this Title, recorded on the National Resilience Ledger,
    and subject to the perpetual stewardship conditions of Section 301(b) of the
    Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act.

(f) PROHIBITION ON PRIVATE CORRECTIONAL CONTRACTS.-- Effective on the date of
enactment of this Act:

    (1) no federal agency shall enter into any new contract with any private
    entity for the operation of a correctional facility, the provision of
    correctional officer services, or the administration of any program
    functioning as a substitute for direct federal correctional operation;

    (2) all existing contracts with private correctional entities shall be
    terminated at the earlier of their current expiration date or the
    decommissioning date of the facility to which they pertain; and

    (3) no private correctional entity, and no affiliate, subsidiary, or
    successor entity of a private correctional entity, shall be eligible to
    provide any service, receive any contract, or hold any governance role within
    any Resilience Campus or Qualified Federated Network established under this
    Act.

