SEC. 102. RESILIENCE CAMPUS CONVERSION.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) PURPOSE.-- Every federal correctional facility decommissioned pursuant to
Section 101 of this Title shall be converted to a Resilience Campus: a
commons-governed residential and cooperative enterprise community providing
housing, healthcare, education, transitional support, and meaningful work to
Reclaiming Stewards completing Harm Repair Agreements, to Commons Members of
the surrounding Qualified Federated Network, and to members of the broader
community served by the network. The Resilience Campus is not a correctional
institution under a different name. It has no punitive function, no mandatory
residency for any person except as voluntarily agreed in a Harm Repair Agreement,
and no authority to restrict the freedom of movement of any resident. Its
governance is entirely democratic, under the Ostrom Standards of Stewardship,
with residents holding full governance rights equivalent to any other Commons
Member.

(b) TRI-PARTITE COUNCIL FORMATION.-- Upon notification of a facility's
scheduled decommissioning pursuant to Section 101(e)(1) of this Title, the
Office of Federated Stewardship shall initiate the formation of a Tri-Partite
Council for the facility on the following terms:

    (1) COMPOSITION.-- The Tri-Partite Council shall comprise equal
    representation from each of the following three constituencies, with the
    specific number of representatives per constituency determined by the Council
    itself through an initial convening process:

        (A) RECLAIMING STEWARD REPRESENTATIVES -- persons currently in custody
        at the facility being decommissioned, selected by the facility's current
        population through a process organized by the persons in custody
        themselves, without administration involvement, and supplemented, upon
        release of those persons, by formerly incarcerated individuals from the
        surrounding community who have completed or are completing Harm Repair
        Agreements;

        (B) COMMUNITY REPRESENTATIVES -- members of the communities within the
        geographic area surrounding the facility, selected through the
        participatory governance processes of any existing Qualified Federated
        Network or, where no QFN yet exists, through a community assembly
        convened by the Office of Federated Stewardship pursuant to its
        geographic coverage obligations under Section 105(c)(2) of the Federal
        Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act; and

        (C) COOPERATIVE ENTERPRISE REPRESENTATIVES -- representatives of
        cooperative enterprises that commit to operating within the converted
        Resilience Campus, including healthcare cooperatives, food cooperatives,
        educational cooperatives, labor cooperatives, and craft or fabrication
        cooperatives, selected through the governance processes of those
        enterprises.

    (2) AUTHORITY.-- The Tri-Partite Council is the primary governance
    institution of the Resilience Campus conversion process. It holds authority
    to:

        (A) determine the programming, physical layout, and operational
        priorities of the converted campus, subject to the minimum requirements
        of subsection (d) of this Section;

        (B) select the receiving Qualified Federated Cooperative to which title
        to the facility will transfer pursuant to Section 101(e)(4) of this
        Title, which may be the Tri-Partite Council itself upon achieving QFC
        certification, or an existing QFN in whose governance the Tri-Partite
        Council participates;

        (C) negotiate the terms of any service agreements, cooperative enterprise
        leases, or resource-sharing arrangements governing operations on the
        campus; and

        (D) establish the bylaws of the campus governance structure under the
        Ostrom Standards of Stewardship, subject to certification review by the
        Office of Federated Stewardship or, following the network maturity
        threshold, by the Peer-to-Peer Audit mechanism.

    (3) FORMATION SUPPORT.-- The Office of Federated Stewardship shall provide
    the Tri-Partite Council with Formation Grant funding pursuant to Section
    106(b)(1) of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act,
    legal and technical assistance for governance document drafting, facilitation
    support for the initial convening processes of each constituency, and access
    to Federated Mesh connectivity sufficient for the Council to conduct its
    governance functions digitally prior to the completion of the facility's
    physical conversion.

    (4) PROHIBITION ON FORMER CONTRACTOR INVOLVEMENT.-- No entity that held a
    contract with the Bureau of Prisons or any other federal agency for
    correctional operations at the facility being converted, and no officer,
    director, or principal of any such entity, shall hold any role in the
    Tri-Partite Council, serve as a cooperative enterprise representative on the
    Council, or hold any governance position in the resulting Resilience Campus
    or its associated Qualified Federated Cooperative.

(c) RECEIVING ENTITY AND TITLE TRANSFER.-- The Tri-Partite Council shall
designate the receiving Qualified Federated Cooperative for title transfer
pursuant to Section 101(e)(4) of this Title not less than one hundred eighty
days before the scheduled decommissioning date of the facility. The receiving
entity:

    (1) shall be a certified Qualified Federated Cooperative or shall have
    achieved provisional QFC certification through the expedited pathway of
    Section 103(e) of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives
    Act prior to the transfer date;

    (2) shall have incorporated the Tri-Partite Council's representation
    structure into its governing bylaws, ensuring that Reclaiming Steward
    representation, community representation, and cooperative enterprise
    representation are permanent structural features of the campus governance
    architecture; and

    (3) shall have executed a Perpetual Stewardship Agreement with the Office of
    Federated Stewardship confirming that the campus land and infrastructure will
    be held in commons stewardship in perpetuity pursuant to Section 301(b) of
    the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act, and will revert
    to the nearest certified Qualified Federated Network upon dissolution of the
    receiving cooperative.

(d) MINIMUM CAMPUS PROGRAMMING REQUIREMENTS.-- Every converted Resilience Campus
shall provide, at minimum, the following programming and infrastructure, which
together constitute the campus's delivery of the Guaranteed Provision Standard
to its residents:

    (1) HOUSING.-- Permanent, secure, non-institutional residential units meeting
    the housing standard of Section 203 of Title II of the Federal Resilience and
    Decentralization Initiatives Act. No residential unit on a Resilience Campus
    shall be designed, furnished, or operated in a manner that replicates the
    conditions of a correctional cell. The Tri-Partite Council shall determine
    the specific residential architecture, with the requirement that all units
    provide private space, natural lighting, and access to outdoor areas.

    (2) HEALTHCARE.-- A cooperative healthcare facility operating under the
    healthcare standard of Section 205 of Title II of the Federal Resilience and
    Decentralization Initiatives Act, with particular capacity for mental health
    services, substance use treatment, and trauma-informed care, recognizing that
    the population transitioning through Resilience Campuses carries
    disproportionate burdens of untreated mental health conditions and
    trauma resulting from both pre-incarceration circumstances and the
    experience of incarceration itself.

    (3) EDUCATION AND SKILL DEVELOPMENT.-- Access to the Intellectual Property
    Commons and cooperative educational programming pursuant to Section 207 of
    Title II of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act,
    including apprenticeship pathways within the cooperative enterprises operating
    on the campus, literacy and numeracy support for residents who need it, and
    legal literacy programming to support Reclaiming Stewards in understanding
    and exercising their rights under this Act.

    (4) COOPERATIVE ENTERPRISE SPACE.-- Physical infrastructure dedicated to the
    operation of cooperative enterprises by campus residents, including workshop
    and fabrication space, agricultural or horticultural space where the site
    permits, commercial kitchen facilities, and co-working infrastructure for
    digital and creative work.

    (5) COMMUNITY SPACE.-- Indoor and outdoor common areas designed for community
    gathering, cooperative governance meetings, cultural programming, and the
    informal social life that constitutes the primary medium through which the
    Accountability Pod process described in Title II of this Act functions.

    (6) CONNECTIVITY.-- Full Federated Mesh Open Standard connectivity throughout
    the campus, providing every resident with access to the National Resilience
    Ledger, the Intellectual Property Commons, the Accountability Coordination
    DAO processes of Title II of this Act, and the governance platforms of the
    campus's Qualified Federated Cooperative.

(e) ANTI-INSTITUTIONAL DESIGN MANDATE.-- The physical conversion of correctional
facilities to Resilience Campuses shall be governed by the following design
mandate: every design decision shall move the campus away from institutional
architecture and toward residential and community architecture. Specifically:

    (1) all security fencing, walls, towers, and perimeter infrastructure
    designed to prevent egress shall be removed prior to occupancy;

    (2) all surveillance infrastructure -- including cameras, monitoring systems,
    and tracking equipment -- that was installed for correctional purposes shall
    be removed or decommissioned prior to occupancy, with new surveillance
    infrastructure permissible only where explicitly authorized by the Tri-Partite
    Council for a defined safety purpose and governed by the privacy protections
    of Title IV of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act;

    (3) residential units shall be reconfigured to provide private, lockable
    space under the resident's own control; and

    (4) the campus shall be open to entry and exit by residents, community
    members, and visitors at all hours, consistent with the governance norms
    established by the Tri-Partite Council, without requirement of authorization,
    pass, or escort.

(f) STEWARDSHIP CREDIT ISSUANCE FOR CAMPUS CONVERSION.-- Upon the recording of
title transfer to a Resilience Campus receiving entity on the National Resilience
Ledger, the Ledger shall automatically issue Stewardship Credits to the receiving
entity pursuant to Section 603 of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization
Initiatives Act, in an amount determined by the assessed productive potential of
the converted facility for residential, cooperative enterprise, educational, and
healthcare functions, as evaluated by the Office of Federated Stewardship in
consultation with the Tri-Partite Council.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 103. FEDERATED COMMONS MEMBERSHIP UPON RELEASE.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) IMMEDIATE AND UNCONDITIONAL ENTITLEMENT.-- Every person released from
federal correctional custody -- whether through completion of sentence, the
Second Look process of Section 104 of this Title, entry into a Harm Repair
Agreement under Title II of this Act, or any other mechanism -- shall be entitled
to immediate and unconditional Federated Commons Membership upon release,
including immediate access to the full Guaranteed Provision Standard. This
entitlement:

    (1) is not conditional upon the person's prior offense, the length of their
    sentence, the nature of the harm they caused, or their current status under
    a Harm Repair Agreement;

    (2) is not subject to a waiting period, application process, or means test;

    (3) activates automatically upon release, with the receiving Qualified
    Federated Network obligated to deliver the full Guaranteed Provision Standard
    within the timeframes established in Section 210 of Title II of the Federal
    Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act;

    (4) includes immediate access to the housing component of the Guaranteed
    Provision Standard, with the receiving network providing interim housing
    meeting the minimum safety standards of Section 203(a)(1) of that Act within
    seventy-two hours of release where permanent housing is not immediately
    available; and

    (5) is portable within the Federated Network on the same terms applicable to
    all Commons Members pursuant to Section 210 of Title II of the Federal
    Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act.

(b) CHOICE OF RECEIVING NETWORK.-- A person released from federal correctional
custody shall have the right to choose the Qualified Federated Network in which
they establish their initial Federated Commons Membership, subject only to the
network's capacity to deliver the Guaranteed Provision Standard. Where a person's
community of origin, family relationships, or existing cooperative affiliations
are located within a specific network's geographic area, placement in that
network shall be given priority. No person shall be placed in a network against
their expressed preference where an alternative network has capacity.

(c) COMMONS MEMBERSHIP RECORD ESTABLISHMENT.-- The Bureau of Prisons shall
establish a Commons Membership Record for every person in federal custody at the
time of enactment of this Act, and for every person entering federal custody
thereafter, recording the person's cryptographic identity, the network in which
they intend to establish membership upon release, and any attribution
registrations in the Intellectual Property Commons made during the period of
custody. This record shall be held by the person in their own custody pursuant
to Section 209 of Title II of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization
Initiatives Act, not by the Bureau of Prisons, and shall be transferable to the
receiving network upon release through the portability mechanisms of that Act.

(d) PRE-RELEASE TRANSITION SUPPORT.-- In the period preceding a person's
release from federal correctional custody, the Bureau of Prisons shall provide:

    (1) access to Federated Mesh connectivity and the National Resilience Ledger
    sufficient to establish the person's Commons Membership Record, identify their
    receiving network, and initiate contact with that network's transition support
    services, not less than one hundred eighty days before the anticipated
    release date;

    (2) facilitated introduction to the Accountability Coordination DAO of the
    person's intended receiving network, enabling the initiation of any Harm
    Repair Agreement process prior to release where the person wishes to begin
    that process; and

    (3) information about the cooperative enterprises, educational programming,
    and community resources available within the receiving network, provided in
    plain language, in the person's primary language, and in accessible formats
    for persons with disabilities or limited literacy.

(e) PROHIBITION ON SUPERVISED RELEASE CONDITIONS INCONSISTENT WITH COMMONS
MEMBERSHIP.-- No condition of supervised release, probation, or parole imposed
in connection with a federal sentence shall:

    (1) restrict a person's access to the Guaranteed Provision Standard or to
    any component of their Federated Commons Membership;

    (2) prohibit a person from residing in a Community Land Trust dwelling,
    participating in a cooperative enterprise, or engaging in cooperative
    governance processes;

    (3) require a person to obtain permission before changing their place of
    residence within the Federated Network; or

    (4) subject a person to electronic monitoring, location tracking, or
    surveillance through the Federated Mesh infrastructure of any Qualified
    Federated Network.

(f) INITIAL COMMONS CREDIT ALLOCATION.-- Every person establishing Federated
Commons Membership upon release from federal correctional custody shall receive,
in addition to the baseline Commons Credit allocation established under Section
607 of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act, a
Reintegration Credit -- a supplemental Commons Credit allocation sufficient to
cover the costs of:

    (1) basic personal goods, tools, and materials needed to establish a
    functioning household within the receiving network's Community Land Trust;

    (2) participation in the first cooperative enterprise of the person's choice
    within the Federated Network, including any membership fee or initial
    contribution required by that enterprise; and

    (3) any transportation costs associated with relocating to the receiving
    network.

    The Reintegration Credit shall be issued automatically by the National
    Resilience Ledger upon recording of the person's Commons Membership in the
    receiving network, and shall not be subject to any condition, repayment
    obligation, or reduction on account of the person's offense history.

