SEC. 104. THE SECOND LOOK MANDATE.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) FINDING.-- Congress finds that a substantial portion of the current federal
prison population is serving sentences that, assessed under the transformative
justice principles and the material conditions infrastructure of this Act, are
longer than necessary to serve any legitimate purpose of community safety and
that, if imposed today, would not be imposed in their current form. The Second
Look Mandate established by this Section requires the systematic review of all
federal sentences to identify persons whose sentences should be reduced or whose
release should be authorized under the framework this Act establishes.

(b) RESENTENCING REVIEW COMMISSION.-- There is established the Federal
Resentencing Review Commission, an independent body within the judicial branch,
comprising:

    (1) nine members appointed by the Chief Justice of the United States in
    consultation with the Judicial Conference, with demonstrated expertise in
    sentencing law, criminal justice reform, restorative justice, and community
    safety research;

    (2) not fewer than three members who are formerly incarcerated persons,
    appointed through a process that includes nominations from organizations
    representing the interests of currently and formerly incarcerated persons;

    (3) not fewer than two members who are representatives of communities most
    affected by mass incarceration, appointed in consultation with civil rights
    organizations and advocacy groups; and

    (4) no member who is a current or former employee of the Bureau of Prisons,
    a current or former federal prosecutor, or a current or former employee of
    any private correctional entity.

(c) REVIEW CRITERIA.-- The Resentencing Review Commission shall review all
federal sentences currently being served and shall recommend reduction or release
for any person whose sentence, assessed under the following criteria, is longer
than the minimum consistent with community safety:

    (1) the person's controlling offense is a non-violent offense as defined in
    Section 101(b)(1)(A) of this Title;

    (2) the person has served not less than one-third of their imposed sentence
    and has not incurred a documented finding of serious physical harm to another
    person during their period of custody;

    (3) the person has a viable Federated Commons Membership placement available
    pursuant to Section 103 of this Title, with housing, healthcare, and community
    support identified;

    (4) the person has expressed willingness to enter a Harm Repair Agreement
    pursuant to Title II of this Act where the nature of the original harm permits
    such an agreement; or

    (5) the person is fifty-five years of age or older and has served not less
    than one-half of their imposed sentence, in recognition of the substantially
    diminished risk of further harm associated with age and the substantial cost
    of providing adequate healthcare to aging incarcerated persons in correctional
    settings.

(d) PROCESS.-- The Resentencing Review Commission shall:

    (1) complete an initial review of all persons currently in federal custody
    within two years of the date of enactment of this Act, with priority given to
    persons in Tier 1 facilities scheduled for decommissioning pursuant to Section
    101(b)(1) of this Title;

    (2) conduct reviews through a process that provides each person in custody
    with notice of their review, the opportunity to submit a personal statement
    and supporting materials, and the assistance of a legal advocate if desired;

    (3) issue written findings for each reviewed person, specifying whether
    reduction or release is recommended and, where it is not, the specific safety
    finding that justifies continued incarceration; and

    (4) transmit its recommendations to the sentencing court, which shall act on
    each recommendation within ninety days through the resentencing procedures
    established under 18 U.S.C. section 3582 as amended by Section 1105 of Title
    XI of this Act.

(e) RETROACTIVE APPLICATION.-- The Second Look Mandate applies retroactively to
all persons currently serving federal sentences, including sentences imposed prior
to the date of enactment of this Act. No statute of limitations, procedural bar,
or doctrine of finality of judgment shall prevent the review of any sentence
under this Section.


================================================================================
TITLE II -- RESTORATIVE JURISPRUDENCE
================================================================================

The purpose of this Title is to establish the substantive architecture of the
transformative justice system that replaces the punitive mechanisms this Act
dismantles. Where Title I addresses the physical and institutional infrastructure
of the prior system, this Title addresses its logic: the rules by which harm is
assessed, accountability is structured, and the pathway back to full community
membership is defined. The central instruments of this Title are the
Accountability Pod, the Harm Repair Agreement, and the Accountability
Coordination DAO. Each reflects a distinct and irreducible function: the Pod
provides the relational human container within which accountability becomes
possible; the Agreement provides the documented structure through which
accountability is expressed and tracked; the DAO provides the technical
coordination layer through which the process is registered, resourced, and
connected to the broader commons infrastructure. None of these instruments is
punitive. None results in incarceration, forced labor, or the permanent marking
of any person as categorically outside the community. The logic of this Title
is restoration: the repair of the harm, the transformation of the conditions
that produced it, and the full return of every participant to commons membership
and community life.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 201. ABOLITION OF EXTRACTIVE MONETARY ASSESSMENTS.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) ABOLITION.-- Effective on the date of enactment of this Act, the following
monetary assessments are abolished in all federal criminal proceedings and in all
proceedings conducted under this Act:

    (1) all fines imposed as punishment for a criminal offense, except as
    specifically preserved under subsection (b) of this Section;

    (2) all fees, surcharges, court costs, and administrative assessments imposed
    on defendants, persons under supervision, or persons in custody in connection
    with any criminal proceeding, including filing fees, public defender
    repayment requirements, probation and parole supervision fees, electronic
    monitoring fees, and fees for the provision of any service that the
    government is constitutionally or statutorily obligated to provide;

    (3) all civil asset forfeiture actions brought by federal law enforcement
    agencies against any person who has not been convicted of a criminal offense,
    and all civil asset forfeiture actions against property whose connection to
    any criminal offense has not been established beyond a reasonable doubt in a
    judicial proceeding in which the property owner had notice and an opportunity
    to be heard; and

    (4) all monetary bail requirements imposed as a condition of pretrial release
    in any federal proceeding.

(b) PRESERVATION OF RESTITUTION IN SPECIFIC CIRCUMSTANCES.-- Nothing in this
Section shall be construed to abolish the obligation of a person who has caused
documented financial harm to another person to make restitution to that person
for the specific financial loss caused, provided that:

    (1) the restitution obligation is established through the Harm Repair
    Agreement process of Section 204 of this Title or through a judicial
    proceeding in which the amount of financial loss is specifically established
    by evidence, not estimated or presumed;

    (2) the restitution obligation is denominated in Commons Credits where the
    harmed party consents to Commons Credit restitution, and in United States
    dollars only where the harmed party specifically requests dollar restitution
    or where the financial loss occurred in a context outside the commons economy;

    (3) the restitution obligation does not bear interest, does not accrue
    penalties for non-payment, and is not enforceable through incarceration; and

    (4) the restitution amount is calibrated to the actual financial loss
    experienced by the harmed party and is not inflated by multipliers, punitive
    enhancements, or amounts designed to serve any purpose other than making the
    harmed party whole.

(c) EXISTING ASSESSMENTS.-- All monetary assessments described in subsection
(a) of this Section that are currently outstanding against any person --
whether imposed by judgment, administrative order, or any other mechanism --
are hereby discharged, and the United States and all instrumentalities
thereof are permanently barred from collecting them, effective on the date
of enactment of this Act. This subsection operates as a waiver and discharge
of the debt owed to the United States and does not direct the vacatur of any
judicial judgment. No collection action, wage garnishment, property lien,
license suspension, or other enforcement measure shall be taken after the
date of enactment to collect any assessment discharged by this Section.

(d) PROHIBITED BAIL ALTERNATIVES.-- The abolition of monetary bail under
subsection (a)(4) of this Section shall not be substituted by non-monetary
conditions of pretrial release that function as de facto detention, including
electronic monitoring requirements that restrict a person's freedom of movement
to a degree equivalent to incarceration, mandatory check-in requirements that
interfere with a person's ability to maintain employment or family relationships,
or any other condition whose primary effect is the surveillance or control of the
person rather than the assurance of their appearance at required proceedings.

(e) CONFORMING PROVISION.-- The imposition of any monetary assessment abolished
by this Section after the date of enactment, by any federal court, federal
agency, or federal officer, shall be void ab initio and shall constitute grounds
for immediate vacatur upon application by the affected person in any federal
court of competent jurisdiction, without requirement of bond or showing of
prejudice.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 202. THE REPARATIVE JUSTICE COMMISSION.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) ESTABLISHMENT.-- There is established the Reparative Justice Commission, an
independent body charged with assessing the historical Reparative Debt owed by
the federal government and, where applicable, by state governments and private
institutions, to communities subjected to systematic policy-driven harm, and with
determining the appropriate issuance of Reparative Stewardship Credits pursuant
to Section 606 of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act.

(b) COMPOSITION.-- The Reparative Justice Commission shall comprise:

    (1) fifteen members appointed jointly by the President and the congressional
    leadership of both chambers through a process requiring bipartisan
    concurrence, of whom:

        (A) not fewer than five shall be members of communities documented to
        have been subjected to the categories of systematic harm described in
        Finding 18 of Section 3 of this Act, selected through a process that
        includes nominations from community-based organizations, tribal
        governments, and civil rights organizations representing those
        communities;

        (B) not fewer than three shall be historians, economists, or social
        scientists with documented expertise in the study of the specific harms
        to be assessed by the Commission; and

        (C) not fewer than two shall be legal scholars with expertise in
        reparations law, constitutional law, and the law of governmental
        liability.

    (2) No member shall be a current or former employee of any federal law
    enforcement agency, the Bureau of Prisons, or any private correctional
    entity.

(c) MANDATE.-- The Reparative Justice Commission shall:

    (1) conduct comprehensive hearings, open to public participation and
    accessible through the participatory governance tools established under Title
    VII of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act, in which
    affected communities present testimony regarding the specific harms they have
    experienced and the forms of reparative recognition they seek;

    (2) assess, on the basis of historical evidence, the causal relationship
    between specific federal governmental policies and the documented material
    harms experienced by specific communities, including the loss of land and
    wealth, the disruption of family and community structures, the denial of
    economic opportunity, and the extraction of labor and resources;

    (3) determine, for each documented community, the appropriate issuance of
    Reparative Stewardship Credits pursuant to Section 606(c) of the Federal
    Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act, denominated in a manner that
    reflects the scope of documented harm and the productive capacity needed to
    address it; and

    (4) issue a comprehensive report within four years of its establishment,
    recorded on the National Resilience Ledger, with findings and recommendations
    that are binding on the Commons Credit Governance Council with respect to
    Reparative Stewardship Credit issuance.

(d) COMMUNITY-CENTERED PROCESS.-- The Reparative Justice Commission's process
shall be governed by the principle that affected communities are the primary
authors of the reparative framework applicable to them. The Commission does not
determine what justice requires for communities in the abstract; it provides the
institutional mechanism through which communities articulate their own claims and
through which those claims are assessed, documented, and translated into the
commons credit architecture that can begin to discharge them.

(e) ONGOING JURISDICTION.-- The Reparative Justice Commission shall maintain
ongoing jurisdiction to assess new claims of systematic governmental harm as they
are presented, and shall conduct comprehensive reviews of prior determinations
not less than once every ten years to assess whether changed circumstances
warrant adjustments to the Reparative Stewardship Credit issuances previously
made.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 203. THE REPARATIVE DEBT FRAMEWORK.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) SCOPE.-- The Reparative Debt framework established by this Section governs
the assessment and discharge of individual accountability for specific harms
occurring within the commons economy, as distinct from the historical
governmental reparative obligations addressed by Section 202 of this Title.
Reparative Debt under this Section arises from documented harm caused by one
person to another person or to a community, assessed through the Accountability
Pod and Accountability Coordination DAO process established in Sections 205 and
206 of this Title.

(b) ASSESSMENT PRINCIPLES.-- The assessment of Reparative Debt shall be governed
by the following principles:

    (1) HARM-CENTERED.-- Reparative Debt is assessed on the basis of the actual
    harm experienced by the harmed party, not on the basis of the category of
    offense, the person's prior history, or any punitive consideration. The
    question the assessment answers is: what does the harmed party need for the
    harm to be genuinely repaired, to the degree that repair is possible?

    (2) PROPORTIONAL.-- The scope of Reparative Debt shall be proportional to
    the documented harm. Debt shall not be inflated by punitive multipliers,
    deterrence considerations, or any factor unrelated to the actual impact of
    the harm on the harmed party and the broader community.

    (3) CONTEXTUAL.-- The assessment shall consider the material and social
    conditions that contributed to the harmful conduct, not to excuse the conduct
    but to ensure that the Harm Repair Agreement addresses those conditions as
    part of the pathway toward genuinely preventing recurrence.

    (4) HARMED PARTY CENTERED.-- The harmed party's own assessment of what repair
    requires shall be the primary input into the Reparative Debt determination.
    No Reparative Debt assessment shall be imposed over the explicit objection of
    the harmed party, and no accountability process shall proceed without the
    harmed party's informed consent.

(c) THE SERVICE RESONANCE RATE.-- Reparative Debt that is not dischargeable
through direct material restitution shall be denominated in units of community
service, valued at the Service Resonance Rate defined in Section 4(17) of this
Act. The Service Resonance Rate:

    (1) applies uniformly to all persons regardless of their prior occupation,
    income, or social status, in express rejection of the principle that a wealthy
    person's hour of community service is worth more than a poor person's;

    (2) is valued at one Commons Credit per hour of verified community service
    performed under a Harm Repair Agreement;

    (3) shall be adjusted by the Commons Credit Governance Council not more than
    once per year, and only to maintain its relationship to the productive output
    of the commons economy, not to alter its fundamental equalization principle;
    and

    (4) applies to service performed in any category recognized by the receiving
    Qualified Federated Network's time-banking system pursuant to Section 604 of
    the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act, ensuring that
    the full range of community contributions recognized by the commons economy
    is available as a form of Reparative Debt discharge.

(d) PROHIBITED DEBT CATEGORIES.-- The following shall not constitute Reparative
Debt under this framework and shall not be imposed through any accountability
process under this Act:

    (1) debt for offenses against the state where no identifiable person or
    community has experienced a specific, documentable harm;

    (2) debt denominated in United States dollars imposed against a person who
    lacks the financial resources to pay without forfeiting their access to the
    Guaranteed Provision Standard; and

    (3) debt whose discharge requires labor in any category that the receiving
    network's collective-choice processes have designated as exploitative,
    degrading, or inconsistent with the dignity of the person performing it.

(e) DISCHARGE AND ERASURE.-- Reparative Debt is fully discharged upon the
completion of the Harm Repair Agreement. Upon discharge:

    (1) the record of the harm and the accountability process shall be sealed on
    the National Resilience Ledger pursuant to Section 207 of this Title, with
    no component accessible to any party other than the person themselves without
    their explicit consent;

    (2) no Qualified Federated Cooperative, Qualified Federated Network, employer,
    housing provider, or any other party within or outside the commons economy
    shall deny any person housing, employment, cooperative membership, or any
    other opportunity on the basis of a sealed accountability record; and

    (3) the person's Federated Commons Membership, if it was suspended during the
    accountability process, shall be fully restored with no diminution of any
    provision component or governance right.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 204. HARM REPAIR AGREEMENTS.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) GENERAL CHARACTER.-- A Harm Repair Agreement is the primary instrument of
individual accountability under this Act. It is a voluntary, documented agreement
between a person who has caused harm and the person or community that experienced
that harm, reached through the Accountability Pod process described in Section
205 of this Title and registered through the Accountability Coordination DAO
described in Section 206 of this Title. A Harm Repair Agreement is not a plea
agreement, a consent decree, a court order, or any other instrument of the
punitive justice system. It does not require judicial approval to take effect and
does not result in a criminal conviction or any other governmental determination
of legal guilt.

(b) CONTENTS.-- A Harm Repair Agreement shall specify:

    (1) a description of the harm that occurred, expressed in terms agreed upon
    by both the person who caused the harm and the harmed party, with the
    harmed party's account taking precedence where the accounts differ;

    (2) the specific acts of repair, service, material restitution, or community
    contribution that the person who caused the harm agrees to undertake, stated
    with sufficient specificity to be verifiable;

    (3) the timeline for completion of each component of the agreement, which
    shall be realistic given the person's circumstances and shall not be so
    compressed as to be unachievable without forfeiture of other life obligations;

    (4) the metric by which completion of each component will be verified, which
    shall rely on human confirmation by the Accountability Pod or the harmed
    party rather than on automated compliance monitoring except where the parties
    explicitly consent to automated verification for a specific component;

    (5) the process that will apply if the person who caused harm encounters
    obstacles to completion, including the Slip Clause required by subsection (d)
    of this Section;

    (6) the conditions under which the agreement shall be deemed fulfilled and
    the record sealed pursuant to Section 207 of this Title; and

    (7) a root-cause assessment: a description, developed collaboratively by the
    Accountability Pod, the person who caused harm, and the harmed party where
    willing, of the material, social, or relational conditions that contributed
    to the harm occurring, together with a plan for how the commons community will
    address those conditions through Bootstrap Grants, cooperative membership,
    healthcare access, or other available mechanisms.

(c) VOLUNTARINESS REQUIREMENT.-- A Harm Repair Agreement is valid only if it
is entered into freely, without coercion, threat, or inducement other than the
genuine desire of the person who caused harm to take accountability. Specifically:

    (1) no person shall be pressured to enter a Harm Repair Agreement as a
    condition of avoiding incarceration, where the threat of incarceration itself
    constitutes the pressure;

    (2) no person shall be denied access to the Guaranteed Provision Standard as
    a means of inducing entry into a Harm Repair Agreement; and

    (3) any person who enters a Harm Repair Agreement shall have the right to
    withdraw from the agreement at any time, with withdrawal resulting in the
    resumption of whatever legal process was underway prior to the agreement,
    if any, without prejudice from the contents of the agreement.

(d) THE SLIP CLAUSE.-- Every Harm Repair Agreement shall contain a Slip Clause
providing that:

    (1) if the person who caused harm fails to complete a component of the
    agreement on the agreed timeline, or engages in conduct inconsistent with the
    spirit of the agreement, this failure shall be treated as information for the
    Accountability Pod rather than as a trigger for automatic consequences;

    (2) the Accountability Pod shall convene within fourteen days of any reported
    non-completion to assess the circumstances, distinguish between non-completion
    attributable to changed circumstances beyond the person's control and
    non-completion attributable to lack of good-faith effort, and determine
    whether and how the agreement should be modified;

    (3) no automated system, including the Accountability Coordination DAO's
    technical layer, shall impose any consequence on the person who caused harm
    as a result of non-completion without a prior human determination by the
    Accountability Pod pursuant to paragraph (2) of this subsection; and

    (4) the Slip Clause may not be waived by any party and may not be overridden
    by any provision of any Harm Repair Agreement.

(e) MULTI-PARTY AGREEMENTS.-- Where a harm has affected multiple persons or a
broader community, a Harm Repair Agreement may be structured as a multi-party
agreement with representation from each affected party. In such cases:

    (1) the agreement requires the genuine participation and consent of all
    represented parties, with no party's consent substituted by a representative's
    judgment unless the party has specifically authorized that representation;

    (2) the Accountability Pod for a multi-party agreement shall include
    representatives connected by genuine relational trust to each of the
    represented parties; and

    (3) the agreement shall address the specific harm experienced by each party
    rather than treating the community harm as an undifferentiated aggregate.

(f) REGISTRATION.-- Upon the parties' execution of a Harm Repair Agreement, the
agreement shall be registered through the Accountability Coordination DAO
pursuant to Section 206 of this Title, with the following information recorded
on the National Resilience Ledger in encrypted form accessible only to the
parties, the Accountability Pod, and the relevant Accountability Coordination
DAO:

    (1) the existence of the agreement and its registration date;

    (2) the completion milestones and their target dates; and

    (3) the cryptographic identities of the parties and Pod members, without
    disclosure of their legal names or other personally identifying information
    to any party outside the process.

    No content of a Harm Repair Agreement, and no information about the harm
    that gave rise to it, shall be recorded on the National Resilience Ledger in
    any form accessible to parties outside the process without the explicit,
    specific, and revocable consent of all parties.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 205. THE ACCOUNTABILITY POD.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) DEFINITION AND AUTHORIZATION.-- The Accountability Pod is hereby authorized
as the primary human institution of the transformative justice architecture
established by this Act. An Accountability Pod is a small group of persons,
united by genuine relational trust with the person who has caused harm, who
commit to supporting that person through the accountability process established
by a Harm Repair Agreement, holding the person accountable to their commitments,
and assisting in addressing the material and relational conditions that
contributed to the harm. The Accountability Pod is not a governmental body, is
not a committee of a Qualified Federated Network, and is not a subunit of the
Accountability Coordination DAO. It is a human relationship structure that
precedes and exceeds any formal governance architecture, constituted voluntarily
by persons who know and are committed to the person who caused harm.

(b) COMPOSITION.-- The composition of an Accountability Pod shall be determined
by the person who caused harm, in consultation with the Accountability
Coordination DAO facilitator, on the basis of genuine relational trust. No
statute, regulation, or governance rule shall prescribe the number of Pod
members, the specific roles they hold, or the demographic composition of the
Pod. What the law requires is the quality of relationship, not its form. A Pod
is adequate when it comprises persons whose genuine commitment to the person who
caused harm is established through their existing relationships, not through
appointment, professional obligation, or governance assignment. The following
requirements apply:

    (1) every Pod member must participate voluntarily, without coercion or
    administrative pressure;

    (2) at least one Pod member must hold a connection to the harmed party or to
    the community affected by the harm, where such a person is willing to
    participate, ensuring that the harmed party's perspective is represented
    within the Pod's deliberations; and

    (3) no Pod member shall be a current law enforcement officer, a current
    employee of the Bureau of Prisons, a current employee of any private
    correctional entity, or a person whose participation is required by any
    condition of supervised release, probation, or parole.

(c) FUNCTIONS.-- The Accountability Pod performs the following functions in the
accountability process:

    (1) CONTAINER.-- The Pod provides the relational container within which the
    person who caused harm can engage honestly with the consequences of their
    conduct, without the fear of permanent judgment or abandonment that prevents
    genuine accountability in adversarial processes. The Pod's commitment to the
    person is unconditional with respect to relationship and conditional with
    respect to behavior: the Pod does not abandon the person if they struggle,
    but it also does not excuse harmful behavior or enable its continuation.

    (2) SUPPORT.-- The Pod assists the person who caused harm in fulfilling the
    commitments of their Harm Repair Agreement, including by connecting them with
    material resources through the commons infrastructure, accompanying them to
    community service commitments, and providing the sustained presence that
    prevents isolation and relapse.

    (3) ACCOUNTABILITY.-- The Pod holds the person who caused harm accountable to
    their commitments through ongoing relationship rather than through reporting,
    surveillance, or punitive consequence. Where the person struggles to meet
    their commitments, the Pod convenes to understand the obstacles and determine
    how the community can address them, invoking the Slip Clause of Section
    204(d) of this Title where necessary.

    (4) ROOT-CAUSE ENGAGEMENT.-- The Pod participates in the root-cause assessment
    required under Section 204(b)(7) of this Title and works with the person and
    the commons infrastructure to address the material, social, and relational
    conditions that contributed to the harm. This function connects the Pod
    directly to the Bootstrap Grant, cooperative membership, healthcare access,
    and other commons provision mechanisms that can address those conditions.

    (5) COMPLETION VERIFICATION.-- The Pod verifies the completion of Harm Repair
    Agreement milestones through the Accountability Coordination DAO's registry
    function, providing the human confirmation required by Section 204(b)(4) of
    this Title. The Pod's verification is the governing determination of
    completion; no automated system shall override a Pod's determination that a
    milestone has been fulfilled.

(d) POD SUPPORT AND TRAINING.-- Every Qualified Federated Network shall provide
the following support to Accountability Pods operating within its boundaries:

    (1) facilitation support from persons trained in transformative justice
    practice, available upon request to any Pod that needs assistance navigating
    a difficult accountability process, but not mandated where the Pod is
    functioning well independently;

    (2) access to commons resources -- including Bootstrap Grants, cooperative
    enterprise referrals, healthcare cooperative access, and housing support --
    to address the material conditions identified in the root-cause assessment;

    (3) access to the Accountability Coordination DAO's coordination
    infrastructure for agreement registration, milestone tracking, and
    resource coordination; and

    (4) a peer network connecting Pod members with other current and former Pod
    members who can share experience and provide mutual support, accessible
    through the Intellectual Property Commons educational resources established
    under Section 207 of Title II of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization
    Initiatives Act.

(e) POD MEMBER PROTECTIONS.-- Pod membership shall not:

    (1) create any legal obligation on the Pod member toward any governmental
    authority, including any obligation to report the person who caused harm to
    law enforcement;

    (2) subject the Pod member to any civil or criminal liability arising solely
    from their participation in the Pod, provided they have not themselves
    participated in or facilitated the harmful conduct;

    (3) be used as evidence of association with any criminal conduct in any
    proceeding; or

    (4) be disclosed to any party outside the accountability process without the
    explicit consent of the Pod member.

(f) PODS FOR SERIOUS HARM.-- The Pod structure established by this Section
applies to all categories of harm within the jurisdiction of the Accountability
Coordination DAO established under Section 206 of this Title, including serious
harm. Where the harm is severe, the Pod process is more important, not less:
the relational accountability that the Pod provides is precisely the mechanism
through which genuine transformation becomes possible in cases where punitive
processes have most consistently failed. No category of harm shall be presumptively
excluded from the Pod process, provided that the harmed party consents to its
use and that the process is conducted with the gravity and care that serious harm
requires.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 206. THE ACCOUNTABILITY COORDINATION DAO -- HRCR PROVISIONS.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) RELATIONSHIP TO FRDI ACT PROVISIONS.-- The Accountability Coordination DAO
established under Section 804 of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization
Initiatives Act serves within this Act as the technical coordination and registry
infrastructure for the transformative justice processes established by this
Title. The provisions of Section 804 of the Federal Resilience and
Decentralization Initiatives Act apply in full to Accountability Coordination
DAOs operating under this Act, and this Section supplements those provisions
with requirements specific to the justice functions of this Act. Where any
provision of this Section conflicts with a provision of Section 804 of the
Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act, this Section controls.

(b) JUSTICE-SPECIFIC FUNCTIONS.-- In addition to the functions established
under Section 804 of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives
Act, the Accountability Coordination DAO shall perform the following functions
in the context of this Act:

    (1) INTAKE AND FACILITATION.-- Receive reports of harm from any person within
    the network, provide an initial facilitated conversation between the reporting
    party and the Accountability Coordination DAO facilitator to assess whether the
    Harm Repair Agreement process is appropriate and desired, and initiate the
    Accountability Pod formation process where the reporting party and, where
    applicable, the person who caused harm consent to proceed;

    (2) POD FORMATION SUPPORT.-- Assist the person who caused harm in identifying
    and convening Accountability Pod members, connecting potential Pod members
    with training and support resources, and providing facilitation for the
    initial Pod convening where requested;

    (3) AGREEMENT REGISTRY.-- Register Harm Repair Agreements pursuant to Section
    204(f) of this Title, maintaining encrypted records of agreement existence,
    milestone timelines, and completion status, accessible only to the parties
    and the Pod;

    (4) RESOURCE COORDINATION.-- Coordinate the commons resources identified in
    the root-cause assessment component of each Harm Repair Agreement, connecting
    the person who caused harm with Bootstrap Grants, cooperative enterprise
    opportunities, healthcare access, housing support, and other provisions
    through the Asynchronous Resource Coordination protocol of the Federated Mesh;

    (5) MILESTONE VERIFICATION REGISTRY.-- Record Pod-verified milestone
    completions as they occur, providing an auditable history of the agreement's
    progress that is available to the parties and the Pod but sealed from all
    other parties; and

    (6) COMPLETION AND ERASURE INITIATION.-- Upon the Pod's verification that all
    Harm Repair Agreement milestones have been completed, initiate the record
    sealing process established under Section 207 of this Title.

(c) PROHIBITION ON ALGORITHMIC JUSTICE DETERMINATIONS.-- No automated function
of the Accountability Coordination DAO shall make or contribute to any
determination affecting the rights, standing, or obligations of any person in
the accountability process. Specifically:

    (1) the DAO shall not generate risk scores, recidivism predictions, or any
    other automated assessment of a person's likelihood of causing future harm;

    (2) the DAO shall not trigger any consequence, escalation, or modification
    of a Harm Repair Agreement without a prior human determination by the
    Accountability Pod or, where the Pod is unable to convene, by the
    Human-in-the-Loop Layer established under Section 803 of the Federal
    Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act;

    (3) the DAO's milestone tracking function shall record completions as
    verified by the Pod and flag apparent non-completions for human review; it
    shall not characterize non-completions as violations, defaults, or failures
    without a human determination through the Slip Clause process of Section
    204(d) of this Title; and

    (4) no data generated by the Accountability Coordination DAO in connection
    with any accountability process shall be used to populate, train, or inform
    any Predictive Policing System, recidivism prediction algorithm, or any other
    automated system that makes assessments of individual behavior or risk.

(d) MULTIPLE HARMS AND CONCURRENT AGREEMENTS.-- Where a person is subject to
multiple Harm Repair Agreements arising from separate harms, the Accountability
Coordination DAO shall coordinate the concurrent agreements to ensure that their
combined requirements are achievable within the person's material and temporal
circumstances, that completion timelines do not conflict, and that a single
Accountability Pod, where appropriate, can serve all concurrent agreements.

(e) COMMUNITY HARM PROCEEDINGS.-- Where a harm has affected the broader commons
community rather than a specific identifiable individual, the Accountability
Coordination DAO shall convene a community accountability process through the
collective-choice governance mechanisms of the Qualified Federated Network,
ensuring that the community's voice in the accountability process is represented
through genuine democratic participation rather than through the DAO facilitator
speaking on the community's behalf.

(f) EXTERNAL LEGAL SYSTEM INTERFACE.-- The Accountability Coordination DAO shall
maintain a documented protocol for interfacing with the external legal system in
cases where:

    (1) a harm constitutes a serious federal crime and the harmed party or the
    community chooses to involve law enforcement, in which case the DAO shall
    support the harmed party's choice without directing or pressuring that choice;

    (2) a Harm Repair Agreement is voluntarily presented to a federal court as
    evidence of accountability in a criminal proceeding, with the court treating
    the agreement as a mitigating factor but not as a substitute for any
    constitutional right of the person who caused harm; or

    (3) a person withdraws from a Harm Repair Agreement under Section 204(c)(3)
    of this Title, in which case the DAO shall provide no information about the
    agreement's contents to any law enforcement authority.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 207. THE ERASURE PROVISION.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) AUTOMATIC SEALING UPON COMPLETION.-- Upon the Accountability Coordination
DAO's recording of an Accountability Pod's verification that all components of
a Harm Repair Agreement have been completed, the records of the accountability
process -- including the Harm Repair Agreement, the milestone completion history,
and any records of the harm on the National Resilience Ledger -- shall be
automatically sealed. Sealing means:

    (1) the records are encrypted to a standard accessible only through the
    cryptographic keys of the parties to the agreement and the members of the
    Accountability Pod;

    (2) no search of the National Resilience Ledger by any person, entity, or
    automated system shall return the sealed records as a result;

    (3) the person who completed the agreement shall receive a Completion
    Credential -- a Zero-Knowledge Proof attestation on the National Resilience
    Ledger confirming only that the person holds an active Federated Commons
    Membership with no outstanding accountability obligations, without disclosing
    any information about the nature or history of any prior accountability
    process; and

    (4) the sealed records shall not be unsealed except by the explicit, specific,
    and contemporaneous consent of both the person who caused the harm and the
    harmed party.

(b) PROHIBITION ON POST-ERASURE DISCRIMINATION.-- Following the sealing of
records pursuant to subsection (a) of this Section, no person, cooperative
enterprise, Qualified Federated Network, governmental authority, or any other
entity shall:

    (1) deny any person housing, employment, cooperative membership, educational
    access, or any other opportunity on the basis of sealed accountability
    records;

    (2) require any person to disclose sealed accountability records as a
    condition of any application, membership, or participation;

    (3) use any method -- including data aggregation, background check services,
    or inference from circumstantial information -- to identify, reconstruct, or
    disclose sealed accountability records; or

    (4) treat the possession of a Completion Credential as evidence of any prior
    accountability process or as a basis for any adverse determination.

(c) RELATIONSHIP TO EXTERNAL CRIMINAL RECORDS.-- The sealing of accountability
records under this Section operates independently of any criminal records that
may exist in external governmental databases. Where a person has a criminal
conviction arising from the same conduct addressed by a completed Harm Repair
Agreement:

    (1) the person shall have an affirmative right to petition the sentencing
    court for expungement of the criminal record upon presentation of their
    Completion Credential, and the court shall grant the expungement unless the
    government demonstrates a specific, compelling interest in the record's
    preservation that substantially outweighs the person's interest in erasure;

    (2) the burden of demonstrating a compelling interest shall rest with the
    government, and the standard shall be significantly higher than the general
    interest in maintaining criminal records; and

    (3) the existence of a Completion Credential shall be treated as a
    presumption in favor of expungement that the government must overcome with
    specific evidence.

(d) YOUTH RECORDS.-- Records of accountability processes involving persons who
were under the age of twenty-five at the time of the harm shall be sealed
automatically at the earlier of: the completion of the Harm Repair Agreement
pursuant to subsection (a) of this Section; or the person's twenty-fifth
birthday, provided the person is actively participating in good faith in an
ongoing accountability process. The developmental science of adolescent and
young adult brain development, which establishes that the capacity for risk
assessment, impulse control, and consequence evaluation is not fully developed
until the mid-twenties, provides the empirical basis for this provision.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 208. VICTIM-CENTERED PROTECTIONS.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) PRIMACY OF HARMED PARTY AGENCY.-- The transformative justice architecture
established by this Title exists to serve the needs of persons who have
experienced harm. No provision of this Title shall be construed to require any
harmed party to participate in any accountability process, enter into any Harm
Repair Agreement, have contact with the person who caused them harm, or accept
any outcome that they have not freely chosen. The agency of the harmed party
is paramount throughout.

(b) SPECIFIC PROTECTIONS.-- Every harmed party in any accountability process
under this Act shall be entitled to:

    (1) full information about the Harm Repair Agreement process, the
    Accountability Pod structure, and their rights throughout the process,
    provided in plain language, in their primary language, and in accessible
    formats for persons with disabilities;

    (2) independent support, provided by a person of the harmed party's choosing
    who is not affiliated with the Accountability Coordination DAO or the
    person who caused harm, throughout any process in which the harmed party
    participates;

    (3) the right to decline participation in any process, or to withdraw from
    a process already underway, at any time and without any adverse consequence
    to the harmed party's Federated Commons Membership, provision access, or
    any other right;

    (4) the right to define the terms of any participation they do choose,
    including the right to decline direct contact with the person who caused
    harm while still participating in the outcome determination through
    documentary or representative means;

    (5) the right to have their account of the harm recorded as the primary
    account in any Harm Repair Agreement, with the burden resting on the person
    who caused harm to demonstrate any material inaccuracy; and

    (6) an independent right to Federated Commons Membership and the Guaranteed
    Provision Standard, entirely separate from any accountability process, such
    that the harmed party's material security never depends on their participation
    in or the outcome of any accountability proceeding.

(c) PROHIBITION ON COERCED PARTICIPATION.-- No person shall be pressured,
incentivized, or required to participate in an accountability process under this
Act as a condition of accessing any commons provision, receiving any governmental
service, or fulfilling any legal obligation. The transformative justice
architecture is an offer, not a compulsion. Where any person -- whether a
harmed party or a person who caused harm -- does not wish to engage with the
process, that choice shall be respected without adverse consequence within the
commons framework.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 209. PROSECUTORIAL COOPERATION FOR SERIOUS HARM DIVERSION.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) FINDING.-- Congress finds that the Accountability Pod and Harm Repair
Agreement framework established by this Title is available without
presumptive exclusion to any category of harm, including serious harm,
pursuant to Section 205(f) of this Title, but that this availability has
full practical effect only where the prosecutorial authority with
jurisdiction over a given offense recognizes Pod-based resolution as a
diversion pathway. Congress finds that restorative diversion for serious
and violent offenses has been demonstrated in practice for more than a
decade by Common Justice, operating in Brooklyn and the Bronx, New York,
which has shown this model to be viable for offenses including assault,
robbery, and other violent felonies, with the cooperation of local district
attorneys' offices and the consent of those harmed, but that its
availability has depended on the discretion of individual prosecutorial
offices, exercised case by case in each jurisdiction where similar practice
has since taken root, rather than on any durable institutional pathway
available to a community as a matter of right. This Section is intended to
convert that discretionary cooperation into a standing, voluntary, and
adequately resourced institutional relationship.

(b) MODEL COOPERATION PROTOCOL.-- The Accountability Coordination DAO
Council established under Section 804 of the Federal Resilience and
Decentralization Initiatives Act shall develop and maintain a model
prosecutorial cooperation protocol, available without charge to any
Qualified Federated Network, establishing the general terms under which a
Qualified Federated Network and a state or local prosecutorial office may
recognize Pod and Harm Repair Agreement resolution as an available
diversion pathway for qualifying offenses. The model protocol shall be
treated as an educational and technical resource of the kind made available
under Section 205(d)(4) of this Title, revised periodically to reflect the
accumulated experience of executed protocols under this Section, and shall
not itself create any binding obligation on any Qualified Federated Network
or prosecutorial office.

(c) LOCAL EXECUTION.-- A Qualified Federated Network may negotiate and
execute a prosecutorial cooperation protocol with any state or local
prosecutorial office having jurisdiction within its boundaries, adapting
the model protocol established under subsection (b) of this Section to the
legal requirements, charging practices, and relationships of that
jurisdiction. An executed protocol under this subsection is a matter
between the Qualified Federated Network and the prosecutorial office, and
nothing in this Section requires uniform terms across executed protocols.

(d) SCOPE AND CONSENT.-- A prosecutorial cooperation protocol executed under
this Section may provide for diversion into the Pod and Harm Repair
Agreement framework only where:

    (1) the harmed party consents to the use of that framework, consistent
    with Section 205(f) of this Title;

    (2) the person whose conduct is at issue accepts responsibility for the
    underlying conduct and agrees to participate in the Harm Repair
    Agreement process; and

    (3) the prosecutorial office retains the discretion, exercised on a
    case-by-case basis and consistent with its own charging authority, to
    decline diversion for any individual case notwithstanding the existence
    of an executed protocol.

(e) FEDERAL FUNDING PRIORITY.-- A state or local prosecutorial office that
has executed a protocol under this Section shall receive priority
consideration for funding under the Restorative Practices Pilot Sites
Program established under 34 U.S.C. section 12514, and the Office on
Violence Against Women is encouraged to consider an executed protocol under
this Section as evidence of institutional readiness for purposes of that
program's award criteria. Nothing in this subsection shall be construed to
create a private right of action or an entitlement to funding under that
program.

(f) NO COMPULSION.-- Nothing in this Section shall be construed to:

    (1) require any state or local prosecutorial office to execute a
    protocol under this Section or to recognize Pod-based diversion for any
    category of offense;

    (2) direct, review, or condition any individual charging or diversion
    decision made by a state or local prosecutorial office; or

    (3) preempt, displace, or limit the prosecutorial authority of any
    state or local government under its own law.

(g) REPORTING.-- The Accountability Coordination DAO Council shall report
to Congress not less often than once every four years on the number of
executed protocols under this Section, the categories of offense diverted
under those protocols, and the outcomes of diverted cases, for the purpose
of informing future revision of the model protocol established under
subsection (b) of this Section.


================================================================================
TITLE III -- FEDERATED PEACE-KEEPING TRANSITION
================================================================================

The purpose of this Title is to establish the institutional architecture through
which the community safety functions currently performed by militarized law
enforcement are progressively transferred to democratically governed, non-armed,
community-based institutions operating within the Federated Network. This
transition does not eliminate the capacity to respond to genuine threats to
physical safety. It restructures who holds that capacity, on what terms, under
whose governance, and with what tools. The Peace Keeper established by this
Title is not a police officer under a different name. The Peace Keeper carries
no weapons, holds no arrest authority, and operates entirely within the
governance of the community's Accountability Coordination DAO and Qualified
Federated Network. Where a situation exceeds the Peace Keeper's jurisdiction --
where immediate armed response to active violence is genuinely required -- the
protocols of this Title define the interface with external law enforcement in a
manner that protects both community safety and civil liberties. The goal is a
community safety architecture in which that interface is invoked rarely, because
the material conditions that generate violence have been substantially addressed
by the commons infrastructure this Act and the Federal Resilience and
Decentralization Initiatives Act establish together.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 301. PEACE KEEPER CERTIFICATION AND FUNCTION.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) ESTABLISHMENT.-- Every Qualified Federated Network shall, within two years
of its certification pursuant to Title I of the Federal Resilience and
Decentralization Initiatives Act, establish a Peace Keeper program providing
trained community safety responders available to respond to non-violent
incidents, mental health crises, substance use emergencies, interpersonal
conflicts, and other community safety situations not requiring armed response
within the network's geographic boundaries. The Peace Keeper program is a
mandatory component of QFN certification at the two-year mark, with the Office
of Federated Stewardship providing technical assistance and Bootstrap Grant
funding for program establishment pursuant to Section 106 of that Act.

(b) JURISDICTION.-- Peace Keepers shall have jurisdiction over the following
categories of incident:

    (1) interpersonal conflicts, disputes, and confrontations not involving
    active physical violence or the credible, imminent threat of physical
    violence;

    (2) mental health crises, including acute psychiatric episodes, suicidal
    ideation, and severe emotional distress, where the person in crisis is not
    actively engaged in violence toward another person;

    (3) substance use emergencies, including overdose response, intoxication
    assistance, and crisis intervention for persons in acute substance use
    distress;

    (4) welfare checks on persons who may be in distress, incapacitated, or
    otherwise in need of assistance but not posing a threat to others;

    (5) noise, nuisance, and quality-of-life complaints that do not involve
    credible safety threats;

    (6) non-violent violations of cooperative governance rules that require
    in-person response before formal Accountability Coordination DAO proceedings
    can be initiated; and

    (7) any other situation within the network's boundaries that a reasonable
    community safety protocol would address without armed response.

(c) CERTIFICATION REQUIREMENTS.-- Persons serving as Peace Keepers shall be
certified through a training program established by the Qualified Federated
Network's governance body, meeting the following minimum standards:

    (1) DE-ESCALATION TRAINING.-- Not less than eighty hours of training in
    evidence-based de-escalation techniques, including verbal communication
    strategies, body language and physical presence management, crisis
    intervention frameworks, and the specific de-escalation protocols
    applicable to mental health and substance use emergencies;

    (2) RESTORATIVE JUSTICE TRAINING.-- Not less than forty hours of training
    in restorative and transformative justice principles, the Accountability Pod
    and Harm Repair Agreement frameworks established in Title II of this Act,
    and the community safety philosophy underlying the Peace Keeper program;

    (3) TRAUMA-INFORMED PRACTICE.-- Not less than forty hours of training in
    trauma-informed approaches to community safety response, including the
    recognition of trauma responses in persons in crisis and the communication
    and intervention approaches that avoid re-traumatization;

    (4) MENTAL HEALTH AND SUBSTANCE USE FIRST RESPONSE.-- Not less than sixty
    hours of training in mental health first aid, substance use crisis response
    including overdose recognition and naloxone administration, and the community
    healthcare resources available within the network for follow-up support;

    (5) COMMONS GOVERNANCE LITERACY.-- Not less than twenty hours of training
    in the governance architecture of the Qualified Federated Network, the
    rights of Commons Members, the Accountability Coordination DAO processes,
    and the specific protocols governing the Peace Keeper's interface with the
    external legal system pursuant to Section 305 of this Title; and

    (6) COMMUNITY KNOWLEDGE.-- Demonstrated knowledge of the specific
    communities, cultural contexts, languages, and social dynamics of the
    geographic area within which the Peace Keeper will operate, assessed through
    a process that includes community input in the evaluation.

(d) PROHIBITED EQUIPMENT AND CONDUCT.-- Peace Keepers shall not:

    (1) carry firearms, conducted energy weapons, chemical agents, impact
    munitions, or any other weapon designed to inflict pain, injury, or
    incapacitation;

    (2) physically restrain any person except to prevent immediate serious
    physical injury to that person or to another person who is present, and
    only to the minimum degree necessary for that purpose and for the minimum
    duration before external emergency services can assume responsibility;

    (3) enter any dwelling without the consent of the occupant, except in
    circumstances of documented immediate threat to the life of a person within
    the dwelling;

    (4) conduct any form of surveillance, tracking, or monitoring of any Commons
    Member in connection with their Peace Keeper duties, except through overt
    and consensual means during an active response; or

    (5) provide any information about any Commons Member to any external law
    enforcement agency except in the specific circumstances established under
    Section 305 of this Title.

(e) GOVERNANCE AND ACCOUNTABILITY.-- Peace Keepers shall operate under the
governance authority of the Qualified Federated Network's Accountability
Coordination DAO, subject to the following accountability mechanisms:

    (1) every Peace Keeper response shall be documented in a report submitted
    to the Accountability Coordination DAO within twenty-four hours, recording
    the nature of the incident, the actions taken, and the outcome, with this
    report accessible to the persons involved in the incident and to the
    network's governance body but protected from external disclosure by the
    privacy provisions of Title IV of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization
    Initiatives Act;

    (2) any use of physical restraint by a Peace Keeper shall trigger an
    automatic Human-in-the-Loop review pursuant to Section 803 of the Federal
    Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act within seventy-two hours,
    with the reviewing body including community representatives independent of
    the Peace Keeper program;

    (3) any allegation of conduct by a Peace Keeper inconsistent with the
    requirements of this Section shall be processed through the Accountability
    Pod and Harm Repair Agreement framework of Title II of this Act, with the
    Peace Keeper subject to the same accountability architecture as any other
    Commons Member; and

    (4) Peace Keepers shall be employed by the Qualified Federated Network as
    cooperative enterprise members, not as law enforcement officers, with their
    employment governed by the democratic processes of the network's labor
    cooperative and subject to the same membership standards as all other
    cooperative enterprise members.

(f) COMPENSATION AND COMMONS MEMBERSHIP.-- Peace Keepers shall receive
compensation for their work through the labor cooperative structure of the
Qualified Federated Network, with their compensation meeting the cooperative's
standard labor rates and their Federated Commons Membership entitlements
identical to those of any other Commons Member. No component of Peace Keeper
compensation shall be structured as an incentive for the number of incidents
responded to, the number of persons referred to external law enforcement, or
any other metric that would create an institutional incentive toward over-
intervention.

(g) DEMONSTRATED PRECEDENT.-- Congress finds that the unarmed, integrated
medical and crisis response model established by this Section has been
demonstrated in practice for more than three decades by the CAHOOTS
program, operated in Eugene and Springfield, Oregon by White Bird Clinic,
which at its peak diverted approximately one in four emergency calls that
would otherwise have received an armed police response, at a fraction of
the cost of conventional law enforcement response. Congress further finds
that this program's decline in 2025 resulted not from any failure of the
underlying model but from its dependence on a single, partial municipal
contract and from billing and reporting requirements designed for
conventional clinical service delivery rather than for a zero-barrier
crisis response model. The Peace Keeper program established by this
Section is accordingly structured to avoid these specific failure modes:
Peace Keepers are funded through the mandatory, multi-year Bootstrap Grant
mechanism established under Section 106 of the Federal Resilience and
Decentralization Initiatives Act rather than through a single negotiable
municipal contract, and are employed as cooperative enterprise members
with full Federated Commons Membership entitlements rather than as
contract staff of an organization wholly dependent on that contract for its
continued operation.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 302. COMMUNITY SAFETY INVESTIGATORS.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) ESTABLISHMENT AND FUNCTION.-- Every Qualified Federated Network may
establish a Community Safety Investigator program, through which trained,
non-armed community members conduct evidence-gathering investigations in
connection with specific documented harms for the purpose of supporting
Accountability Pod and Harm Repair Agreement processes under Title II of this
Act. Community Safety Investigators are not law enforcement officers, do not
have arrest authority, and do not operate within the command structure of any
law enforcement agency. Their function is to serve the transformative justice
process, not to build criminal prosecutions.

(b) SCOPE OF INVESTIGATION.-- Community Safety Investigators may:

    (1) gather testimony, documentary evidence, and physical evidence relevant
    to a specific documented harm, with the consent of the persons from whom
    the evidence is gathered;

    (2) document the circumstances and context of a harm in ways that support
    the Harm Repair Agreement process, including the material and social
    conditions relevant to the root-cause assessment;

    (3) compile and present investigative findings to the Accountability
    Coordination DAO and the relevant Accountability Pod; and

    (4) at the request of a harmed party who has chosen to involve external law
    enforcement, assist in compiling documentation to support that party's
    engagement with the external legal system, without themselves initiating or
    directing that engagement.

(c) LIMITATIONS.-- Community Safety Investigators shall not:

    (1) conduct any investigation without the knowledge and consent of the
    persons whose information is being gathered, except where documenting
    physical circumstances at locations accessible to the general public;

    (2) share investigative findings with any external law enforcement agency
    without the explicit consent of all parties whose information is contained
    in those findings;

    (3) use any Predictive Policing System, behavioral analysis tool, or
    automated risk assessment instrument in the course of their investigative
    work; or

    (4) take any action that would compromise the voluntariness of the Harm
    Repair Agreement process or that would convert an accountability process
    into a de facto criminal investigation.

(d) TRAINING AND CERTIFICATION.-- Community Safety Investigators shall complete
a training program established by the Qualified Federated Network's governance
body meeting standards equivalent to those of Section 301(c) of this Title,
with additional training in evidence documentation, privacy-protective
investigative methods, and the specific boundaries between commons-based
investigation and external law enforcement functions.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 303. JURISDICTIONAL TRANSFER PROTOCOL.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) POLICY.-- It is the policy of this Act that non-violent community safety
incidents within the geographic boundaries of a certified Qualified Federated
Network shall be the primary responsibility of the network's Peace Keeper
program rather than of external law enforcement. This transfer of primary
responsibility is a consequence of the material security infrastructure
established by the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act and
the transformative justice architecture established by this Act: as communities
develop the material conditions and governance institutions that address the
structural roots of harmful behavior, the need for external armed intervention
diminishes correspondingly.

(b) DISPATCH PROTOCOL.-- Every Qualified Federated Network shall establish,
within two years of its certification, a community dispatch protocol that:

    (1) receives calls for community safety assistance through a dedicated
    network contact point accessible to all Commons Members;

    (2) routes non-violent incidents within the Peace Keeper's jurisdiction
    pursuant to Section 301(b) of this Title to the network's Peace Keeper
    program as the primary responder;

    (3) routes incidents involving active violence, credible imminent threats of
    serious physical injury, or circumstances requiring immediate armed response
    to external emergency services, with Peace Keepers available to respond
    concurrently in a support and de-escalation capacity where their presence
    would not endanger them or others; and

    (4) maintains documentation of all dispatched incidents and their outcomes,
    recorded on the National Resilience Ledger in aggregated form for network
    governance review, and accessible to the network's Accountability
    Coordination DAO for program assessment and improvement.

(c) INCIDENT CATEGORY STANDARDS.-- The Qualified Federated Network's governance
body shall establish, through its collective-choice processes, specific incident
category standards defining which situations fall within the Peace Keeper's
jurisdiction and which require external law enforcement response. These standards:

    (1) shall be developed with meaningful input from all Commons Members through
    the participatory governance tools of Title VII of the Federal Resilience and
    Decentralization Initiatives Act;

    (2) shall be reviewed annually and updated to reflect the network's evolving
    safety capacity and the outcomes of prior incident responses;

    (3) shall err toward Peace Keeper jurisdiction in ambiguous cases, on the
    empirical finding that armed response to non-violent situations increases
    rather than decreases risk of injury; and

    (4) shall be publicly available to all Commons Members, ensuring that every
    person in the network understands what response to expect in any given
    situation.

(d) EXTERNAL LAW ENFORCEMENT INTERFACE.-- Every Qualified Federated Network
shall establish a written protocol governing the interface between the network's
community safety infrastructure and external federal, state, and local law
enforcement agencies, providing:

    (1) the specific categories of incident in which external law enforcement
    will be contacted by the network's dispatch system;

    (2) the protocols for ensuring that external law enforcement agencies respond
    to network calls in a manner consistent with the rights of Commons Members,
    including the requirement that any law enforcement entry onto Resilience
    Campus property comply with the warrant requirements of the Fourth Amendment
    and the heightened standards of Section 209(e) of the Federal Resilience and
    Decentralization Initiatives Act;

    (3) the designation of a network liaison responsible for communicating with
    external law enforcement on behalf of the network and ensuring that law
    enforcement activity within the network's boundaries is consistent with this
    Act; and

    (4) a process for reviewing and documenting every external law enforcement
    contact within the network's boundaries, with the review conducted by the
    Accountability Coordination DAO and accessible to the Commons Members
    affected.

(e) TRANSITION TIMELINE.-- The transfer of primary community safety
responsibility to the Peace Keeper program shall proceed on the following
timeline:

    (1) within one year of QFN certification: the network shall establish its
    dispatch protocol and begin Peace Keeper recruitment and training;

    (2) within two years of QFN certification: the Peace Keeper program shall
    be operational and shall serve as the primary responder for all non-violent
    incidents within the categories established under subsection (c) of this
    Section;

    (3) within three years of QFN certification: the network shall conduct a
    comprehensive review of the jurisdictional transfer, assessing which
    categories of incident have been successfully managed by the Peace Keeper
    program and whether any categories should be added; and

    (4) on an ongoing basis: the network shall continue expanding the Peace
    Keeper program's capacity and jurisdiction as the material security
    infrastructure of the commons reduces the frequency and severity of harmful
    incidents within the network's boundaries.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 304. PROHIBITION ON PREDICTIVE POLICING AND ALGORITHMIC RISK ASSESSMENT.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) ABSOLUTE PROHIBITION.-- No Peace Keeper, Community Safety Investigator,
Accountability Coordination DAO, Accountability Pod, Qualified Federated
Cooperative, Qualified Federated Network, or any entity exercising any community
safety, justice, or governance function under this Act or the Federal Resilience
and Decentralization Initiatives Act shall use any Predictive Policing System
for any purpose in connection with that function.

(b) SCOPE.-- The prohibition established by this Section applies to:

    (1) any use of a Predictive Policing System to determine which persons or
    communities to monitor, investigate, or respond to preemptively;

    (2) any use of a Predictive Policing System to inform any determination made
    in a Harm Repair Agreement process, including the assessment of Reparative
    Debt, the structure of the agreement's requirements, or the verification of
    completion;

    (3) any use of a Predictive Policing System in the dispatch protocol
    established under Section 303(b) of this Title, including any system that
    allocates Peace Keeper resources based on predicted incident likelihood in
    specific areas;

    (4) any use of a Predictive Policing System to assess any person's eligibility
    for Federated Commons Membership, Resilience Campus residency, or any
    commons provision; and

    (5) any use of a Predictive Policing System by any external law enforcement
    agency in connection with any activity within the geographic boundaries of
    a Qualified Federated Network, to the extent that federal law permits such
    restriction.

(c) PROHIBITION ON DATA PROVISION.-- No Qualified Federated Network, Qualified
Federated Cooperative, Accountability Coordination DAO, or any other entity
operating within the commons infrastructure shall provide data to any external
party for the purpose of training, operating, or improving any Predictive
Policing System. The commons infrastructure data generated under the Federal
Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act -- including ARC protocol data,
Commons Credit transaction records, and governance participation data -- is
explicitly prohibited from use in any Predictive Policing application.

(d) EXISTING CONTRACTS.-- Any existing contract between a Qualified Federated
Network or its constituent cooperatives and any provider of Predictive Policing
System services shall be terminated on the date of the network's certification
or on the date of enactment of this Act, whichever is later. No new contract
for Predictive Policing System services shall be entered into by any entity
operating within the Federated Network after the date of enactment.

(e) ENFORCEMENT.-- Violation of this Section shall constitute:

    (1) a serious violation of the Ostrom Standards of Stewardship subject to
    Level 3 graduated response under Section 103(c)(2)(C) of the Federal
    Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act for a first violation;

    (2) grounds for Level 4 decertification under Section 103(c)(2)(D) of that
    Act for repeated or systematic violations; and

    (3) an independent cause of action for any Commons Member affected by a
    Predictive Policing System determination in any federal court of competent
    jurisdiction, with statutory damages of not less than five thousand dollars
    per violation and not more than fifty thousand dollars per violation, plus
    attorney's fees.

