SEC. 305. COMMUNITY SAFETY INFRASTRUCTURE INVESTMENT.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) FINDING.-- Congress finds that the conditions most predictive of harmful
behavior -- material deprivation, untreated mental health conditions, substance
use disorders, social isolation, and the experience of historical injustice --
are addressed most effectively through investment in the social and material
infrastructure of communities, not through investment in law enforcement and
incarceration. The transformation of federal correctional spending established
by this Act, and the material security infrastructure established by the Federal
Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act, together constitute the most
significant community safety investment in the history of this legislation.
This Section provides for the specific redirection of resources freed by the
decommissioning schedule of Section 101 of Title I of this Act toward the
community safety infrastructure that evidence identifies as most effective.

(b) CORRECTIONAL SAVINGS REINVESTMENT.-- The net budgetary savings realized
through the decommissioning of federal correctional facilities pursuant to
Section 101 of this Title shall be directed, on an annual basis, to the
following community safety infrastructure investments, in the proportions
established by the Commons Credit Governance Council in consultation with the
Reparative Justice Commission:

    (1) not less than forty percent to the Bootstrap Grant Program established
    under Section 106 of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives
    Act, with priority allocation to QFN formation and expansion in communities
    with the highest historical rates of incarceration;

    (2) not less than twenty-five percent to cooperative mental health and
    substance use treatment infrastructure within certified Qualified Federated
    Networks, supplementing the healthcare cooperative provisions of Section 205
    of Title II of that Act with dedicated capacity for the populations most
    likely to transition from Resilience Campuses;

    (3) not less than fifteen percent to Peace Keeper program establishment and
    training, through Bootstrap Grants specifically designated for community
    safety infrastructure under the coverage extension provisions of Section
    105(c)(3) of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act;

    (4) not less than ten percent to the Reparative Justice Commission's
    operations and to the Reparative Stewardship Credit issuances authorized
    under Section 606 of that Act; and

    (5) the remaining amount, not less than ten percent, to the Commons
    Solidarity Fund established under Section 1005 of that Act, recognizing
    that the global conditions that drive migration, displacement, and
    international harm are addressed by the same commons infrastructure
    principles this Act applies domestically.

(c) YOUTH SAFETY INVESTMENT.-- A defined portion of the community safety
infrastructure investment established by subsection (b) of this Section,
not less than twenty percent of the total reinvestment amount, shall be
specifically directed toward youth safety infrastructure, including:

    (1) cooperative after-school and summer programming within certified
    Qualified Federated Networks, providing meaningful creative, educational,
    and productive activities for young people outside school hours;

    (2) apprenticeship pathways connecting young people with cooperative
    enterprises within the Federated Network, providing meaningful work
    experience and the mentorship relationships that the developmental science
    of adolescent safety identifies as among the most powerful protective
    factors against harmful behavior;

    (3) cooperative childcare infrastructure within the Federated Network,
    addressing the documented relationship between inadequate childcare access
    and the economic stress that contributes to family instability and its
    associated harms; and

    (4) restorative circle programming in schools and cooperative educational
    institutions within the network, establishing the conflict resolution skills
    and the experience of genuine accountability from an early age.

(d) MENTAL HEALTH AND SUBSTANCE USE AS SAFETY INFRASTRUCTURE.-- The cooperative
healthcare provisions of Section 205 of Title II of the Federal Resilience and
Decentralization Initiatives Act shall be understood, for the purposes of
community safety investment under this Section, as community safety
infrastructure of the first order. Every dollar invested in accessible,
community-governed, trauma-informed mental health and substance use treatment
within the Federated Network is a community safety investment, addressing the
conditions that generate harmful behavior before those conditions produce harm.
The healthcare cooperative certification requirements of that Act shall include
specific standards for mental health and substance use treatment capacity,
calibrated to the documented mental health and substance use needs of the
communities served by each network.

