SEC. 306. REPEAL OF THE 1033 PROGRAM.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) REPEAL.-- Section 1033 of the National Defense Authorization Act for Fiscal
Year 1997, Public Law 104-201, codified at 10 U.S.C. section 281, which
authorizes the Secretary of Defense to transfer surplus military equipment to
federal and state law enforcement agencies, is hereby repealed effective on the
date of enactment of this Act.

(b) ASSET REPATRIATION.-- All military equipment transferred to federal, state,
and local law enforcement agencies under the authority of the repealed provision
shall be:

    (1) inventoried by each receiving agency within one hundred eighty days of
    the date of enactment of this Act, with the inventory submitted to the
    Secretary of Defense and published in the Federal Register;

    (2) returned to the Department of Defense within three hundred sixty-five
    days of the date of enactment of this Act, except for equipment that has
    been rendered non-operational, destroyed, or irrecoverably integrated into
    civilian law enforcement systems; and

    (3) assessed by the Civilian-Use Board established under Section 902 of
    the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act for potential
    transfer to the Intellectual Property Commons or to Resilience Campus
    infrastructure, consistent with the dual-use technology transfer principles
    of Title IX of that Act.

(c) PROHIBITION ON ALTERNATIVE TRANSFER MECHANISMS.-- No provision of any
federal law shall be construed, after the date of enactment of this Act, to
authorize the transfer of military weapons systems, armored vehicles, aircraft,
or crowd control equipment to any civilian law enforcement agency. The repeal
established by this Section closes the 1033 Program permanently and shall not
be substituted by any equivalent program under a different statutory authority.

(d) STATE AND LOCAL DEMILITARIZATION.-- As a condition of receiving any federal
law enforcement assistance grant or cooperative agreement after the date of
enactment of this Act, state and local law enforcement agencies shall certify
that they have complied with the asset repatriation requirements of subsection
(b) of this Section and that they have adopted use-of-force policies consistent
with the community safety principles of this Act.


================================================================================
TITLE IV -- TRANSFORMATIVE JUSTICE INFRASTRUCTURE
================================================================================

The purpose of this Title is to establish the specialized institutional
infrastructure that the transformative justice architecture requires beyond the
general provisions of Titles I through III: dedicated frameworks for youth
justice, substance use and mental health, community mediation, and the explicit
recognition that the domestic social commons established by this Act and the
Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act is inseparable from its
international dimensions. The provisions of this Title extend the commons
logic into the domains where the punitive system has been most visibly
counterproductive and where the evidence for transformative alternatives is
most robust. Youth incarceration has consistently failed to reduce youth
offending and has consistently succeeded in accelerating life trajectories
toward further harm. Criminalizing mental illness and substance use disorders
has consistently failed to address either condition and has consistently
succeeded in deepening both. The institutions this Title establishes are not
experimental. They reflect the accumulated evidence of decades of practice in
communities and jurisdictions that chose a different path.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 401. TRANSFORMATIVE JUSTICE CENTERS.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) ESTABLISHMENT.-- Every certified Qualified Federated Network shall establish,
within three years of its certification, at least one Transformative Justice
Center: a community-governed facility providing residential transitional
support, mental health and substance use services, cooperative skill development,
restorative justice facilitation, and community connection for persons
transitioning through Harm Repair Agreements, persons leaving Resilience
Campuses, persons in mental health or substance use crisis who need residential
support, and any other community member whose circumstances indicate that a
period of supported community living would reduce the likelihood of harm to
themselves or others. A Transformative Justice Center is not a correctional
facility, a psychiatric institution, or a homeless shelter. It is a supported
commons living environment, governed by its residents under the Ostrom Standards
of Stewardship, oriented entirely toward strengthening the conditions that
enable people to live well in community.

(b) GOVERNANCE.-- Each Transformative Justice Center shall be governed as a
Qualified Federated Cooperative under Title I of the Federal Resilience and
Decentralization Initiatives Act, with:

    (1) a resident governance council comprising persons currently residing at
    the Center, elected by residents through the collective-choice processes of
    Section 102(d) of that Act, holding primary authority over the Center's
    programming, daily operations, community agreements, and resident relations;

    (2) a community advisory body comprising members of the surrounding Qualified
    Federated Network, meeting not less than quarterly to provide input on the
    Center's relationship to the broader community, to advocate for resources
    the Center needs, and to ensure that the Center remains integrated into
    rather than isolated from the surrounding commons; and

    (3) a healthcare cooperative liaison, provided by the cooperative healthcare
    enterprise serving the network, to coordinate the mental health, substance
    use, and general healthcare services delivered at the Center and to ensure
    continuity of care as residents transition in and out.

(c) PROGRAMMING REQUIREMENTS.-- Every Transformative Justice Center shall
provide, at minimum, the following programming, adapted to the specific needs
and preferences of its residents through the resident governance council's
collective-choice processes:

    (1) RESIDENTIAL SUPPORT.-- Private or semi-private residential space meeting
    the housing standard of Section 203 of Title II of the Federal Resilience and
    Decentralization Initiatives Act, with the additional requirement that space
    be designed to support both individual privacy and communal living, reflecting
    the dual needs of persons in transitional circumstances for both solitude
    and belonging;

    (2) MENTAL HEALTH AND SUBSTANCE USE SERVICES.-- On-site access to
    trauma-informed mental health services and substance use treatment, provided
    by the cooperative healthcare enterprise, including peer support specialists
    with lived experience of mental health conditions and substance use recovery,
    who are employed as cooperative enterprise members and whose expertise is
    recognized as professional expertise of the highest relevance to the
    population served;

    (3) ACCOUNTABILITY POD FACILITATION.-- On-site facilitation support for
    Accountability Pods and Harm Repair Agreement processes for residents who
    are engaged in accountability processes under Title II of this Act, with
    physical space designed to support circle and dialogue formats that the
    Pod process requires;

    (4) COOPERATIVE ENTERPRISE PARTICIPATION.-- Integration of the Center with
    the cooperative enterprise ecosystem of the surrounding Qualified Federated
    Network, providing residents with meaningful work opportunities, skill
    development, and the cooperative membership that comes with productive
    participation in the commons economy; and

    (5) COMMUNITY CONNECTION PROGRAMMING.-- Structured and unstructured
    programming oriented toward building and rebuilding community connections
    for residents whose social networks have been disrupted by incarceration,
    mental health crisis, substance use, or other circumstances, including
    community meals, cultural programming, commons governance participation,
    and facilitated introduction to cooperative enterprises and community
    institutions within the network.

(d) VOLUNTARY RESIDENCY.-- Residency at a Transformative Justice Center is
entirely voluntary. No person shall be required to reside at a Center as a
condition of their Harm Repair Agreement, as a condition of release from
federal custody, or as a condition of any other obligation under this Act,
except where the person themselves has chosen residential placement as a
component of their accountability process and the choice is documented as
genuinely voluntary in the Harm Repair Agreement pursuant to Section 204(c)
of Title II of this Act. The Transformative Justice Center shall maintain a
no-discharge-without-consent policy: no resident shall be required to leave
the Center without their consent except where their continued presence poses
a documented immediate threat to the physical safety of other residents, and
only after the Accountability Coordination DAO has exhausted all alternative
responses.

(e) FUNDING AND GOVERNANCE EXCLUSIONS.-- Transformative Justice Centers shall
be funded through the correctional savings reinvestment mechanism of Section
305(b) of Title III of this Act, through Bootstrap Grants pursuant to Section
106 of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act, and through
the cooperative enterprise activities of Center residents whose productive work
generates Commons Credits reinvested in Center operations. No Transformative
Justice Center shall be funded through a contract with any private correctional
entity or any entity affiliated with the private correctional industry. Consistent
with the prohibition established in Section 102(b)(4) of Title I of this Act
with respect to Resilience Campus Tri-Partite Councils, no private correctional
entity, and no officer, director, principal, or affiliate of any private
correctional entity, shall hold any governance role, management position, service
contract, or staffing role within any Transformative Justice Center. This
exclusion applies to entities that held correctional contracts at any point in
the five years preceding the date of enactment, and to any successor, affiliate,
or subsidiary entity of such a contractor, regardless of whether the entity
operates under a different name or corporate form.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 402. COMMUNITY MEDIATION NETWORK.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) ESTABLISHMENT.-- The Office of Federated Stewardship shall, in coordination
with the Qualified Federated Networks established under the Federal Resilience
and Decentralization Initiatives Act, support the development of a Community
Mediation Network: a distributed, community-governed infrastructure of trained
mediators, restorative circle facilitators, and conflict resolution practitioners
available to any person within a Qualified Federated Network's geographic area
who is experiencing a conflict, dispute, or interpersonal harm that they wish
to address through a facilitated process outside of any formal accountability
proceeding.

(b) RELATIONSHIP TO ACCOUNTABILITY PROCESSES.-- The Community Mediation Network
operates alongside and in support of the Accountability Pod and Harm Repair
Agreement processes of Title II of this Act, but is distinct from them. Where
the Accountability Pod process is engaged when a harm has occurred and the
person who caused it is willing to take accountability, the Community Mediation
Network is available for the full range of interpersonal and community conflicts
that do not rise to the level of a formal harm requiring an Accountability Pod,
including:

    (1) neighbor disputes, property boundary disagreements, and shared resource
    conflicts within Community Land Trust communities;

    (2) workplace conflicts and cooperative governance disputes within labor
    cooperatives and other Qualified Federated Cooperatives;

    (3) family and relationship conflicts where the parties seek facilitated
    communication rather than formal accountability;

    (4) conflicts between cooperative enterprises over resource allocation,
    contract performance, or shared infrastructure use; and

    (5) community-level tensions that, if unaddressed, could escalate into
    harmful situations, with the Mediation Network serving as the early
    intervention that prevents escalation.

(c) TRAINING STANDARDS.-- Practitioners in the Community Mediation Network shall
complete training meeting the following minimum standards, established by the
Qualified Federated Network's governance body in consultation with established
community mediation and restorative justice training organizations:

    (1) not less than forty hours of foundational mediation training, covering
    interest-based negotiation, active listening, conflict analysis, and the
    principles of voluntary, self-determined resolution;

    (2) not less than twenty hours of restorative circle facilitation training,
    covering the circle process, the role of the facilitator, and the specific
    dynamics of circle work in community conflict contexts;

    (3) not less than twenty hours of cultural competency training, with specific
    attention to the cultural, linguistic, and experiential diversity of the
    communities served by the network and the mediation approaches appropriate
    to different cultural contexts; and

    (4) ongoing supervised practice not less than twice annually, ensuring that
    mediation skills remain current and that practitioners receive feedback on
    their practice.

(d) ACCESSIBILITY REQUIREMENTS.-- The Community Mediation Network shall be
accessible to all persons within a Qualified Federated Network's geographic
area, without regard to their Commons Membership status, on the following terms:

    (1) services shall be provided at no cost to the parties;

    (2) services shall be available in all languages spoken by more than one
    percent of the network's population, with interpretation services available
    for all other languages upon request;

    (3) services shall be accessible to persons with disabilities, including
    through alternative communication formats, accessible meeting locations, and
    remote participation options; and

    (4) services shall be available in a timely manner, with an initial facilitated
    conversation available within seventy-two hours of a request and a full
    mediation session available within fourteen days.

(e) CONFIDENTIALITY.-- All communications made in the context of a Community
Mediation Network process are confidential and shall not be disclosed to any
external party, including any law enforcement agency, without the explicit
consent of all parties. No statement made in a mediation process shall be
admissible in any judicial or administrative proceeding without the consent
of the party who made the statement. The confidentiality protection established
by this subsection is a condition of the voluntary, self-determined character
of the mediation process and shall be construed broadly in favor of
confidentiality in any proceeding in which it is at issue.

