SEC. 403. YOUTH JUSTICE PROVISIONS.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) FINDING.-- Congress finds that the developing brain of a person under the
age of twenty-five -- including, and most urgently, a person under the age of
eighteen -- operates under biological constraints on impulse control, risk
assessment, and consequence evaluation that are materially different from those
of a fully developed adult brain. The Supreme Court of the United States has
recognized this developmental reality in a series of decisions holding that the
Eighth Amendment prohibits certain categories of punishment as applied to
juveniles. This Act extends that constitutional recognition into the affirmative
design of a youth justice framework that is calibrated from the outset to the
developmental realities of youth, rather than applying an adult punitive system
to young people and then carving out constitutional exceptions at the margins.

(b) JURISDICTIONAL PRESUMPTION.-- For any person under the age of twenty-five
at the time of a harm, there is a strong presumption that the matter falls
within the jurisdiction of the Accountability Coordination DAO and the
Accountability Pod process rather than the external legal system. This
presumption may be rebutted only upon a specific finding by a Human Review
Panel, convened pursuant to Section 803 of the Federal Resilience and
Decentralization Initiatives Act, that:

    (1) the harm involved the use of serious physical force resulting in
    significant injury to another person; and

    (2) the commons accountability process, specifically designed for the
    young person's circumstances and developmental stage, is genuinely
    inadequate to address the safety needs of the community and the harmed
    party.

    The Human Review Panel's finding shall be made on the basis of the
    specific circumstances of the specific person and the specific harm, not
    on the basis of offense category alone.

(c) YOUTH ACCOUNTABILITY PODS.-- Accountability Pods for young persons shall
be constituted with particular attention to the developmental context of
youth accountability, including:

    (1) membership drawn from persons who hold genuine, ongoing relationships
    with the young person, which in the case of young people typically includes
    family members, teachers, coaches, mentors, and peers, with the young
    person's own input into Pod composition given significant weight;

    (2) facilitation by a person with specific training in adolescent and
    young adult development, trauma-informed youth practice, and the specific
    dynamics of accountability processes with young people; and

    (3) a process pace calibrated to the young person's developmental capacity
    for reflection and accountability, which may require more time, more
    repetition, and more relational scaffolding than equivalent processes with
    fully developed adults.

(d) EDUCATION AND OPPORTUNITY AS ACCOUNTABILITY INFRASTRUCTURE.-- For young
persons engaged in accountability processes under this Act, the root-cause
assessment required by Section 204(b)(7) of Title II of this Act shall give
particular attention to educational access, mentorship availability, cooperative
enterprise opportunities, and the social connections that developmental science
identifies as the primary protective factors against harmful behavior in youth.
The Harm Repair Agreement for a young person shall include, as a standard
component, a plan for the young person's ongoing educational engagement and
connection to cooperative enterprise apprenticeship within the Qualified
Federated Network.

(e) PROHIBITION ON YOUTH INCARCERATION IN ADULT FACILITIES.-- No person under
the age of twenty-five shall be held in any federal correctional facility
alongside adults. Effective on the date of enactment of this Act:

    (1) all persons under the age of eighteen currently held in federal adult
    correctional facilities shall be transferred to the custody of the Resilience
    Campus or Transformative Justice Center nearest to their community of origin
    within ninety days, pending the completion of their Second Look review under
    Section 104 of Title I of this Act;

    (2) all persons between the ages of eighteen and twenty-five currently held
    in federal adult correctional facilities shall be reviewed under the Second
    Look Mandate within one year, with the strong presumption established in
    subsection (b) of this Section applied to their circumstances; and

    (3) no person under the age of eighteen shall be held in any federal
    correctional facility for any period following the date of enactment, with
    all such cases transferred immediately to the Accountability Coordination
    DAO jurisdiction of the Qualified Federated Network serving the person's
    community of origin.

(f) YOUTH RECORD PROTECTIONS.-- The youth record protections of Section 207(d)
of Title II of this Act shall apply in full to all persons under the age of
twenty-five engaged in accountability processes under this Act. In addition:

    (1) no accountability record of any person for conduct that occurred before
    the age of eighteen shall ever be unsealed for any purpose;

    (2) no accountability record of any person for conduct that occurred before
    the age of twenty-five shall be considered in any determination affecting
    that person's employment, housing, cooperative membership, or educational
    access after the age of thirty; and

    (3) the expungement right established in Section 207(c) of Title II of this
    Act shall be available without any showing of compelling government interest
    with respect to any criminal record arising from conduct that occurred before
    the age of twenty-five.

