SEC. 404. SUBSTANCE USE AND MENTAL HEALTH DECRIMINALIZATION.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) POLICY.-- It is the policy of this Act that substance use and mental health
conditions are health matters, not criminal matters, and that the resources of
the justice system shall not be directed toward the management of health
conditions that are most effectively addressed through healthcare, peer support,
and the material conditions of stable community life. The provisions of this
Section transfer jurisdiction over substance use and mental health crises from
the criminal legal system to the cooperative healthcare infrastructure
established under the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act.
This policy is grounded in the substantial empirical record of comparative
decriminalization experience. Portugal's 2001 decriminalization of personal
possession of all controlled substances, combined with the redirection of
enforcement resources to health and social services through Dissuasion
Commissions, produced sustained reductions in drug-related HIV transmission,
overdose deaths, incarceration for drug offenses, and drug-related criminal
activity, demonstrating that health-centered responses to substance use generate
better safety outcomes than criminalization. Oregon's Measure 110, enacted in
2020, provides a domestic precedent whose implementation period, including both
its successes and the implementation challenges that preceded full service
infrastructure buildout, informs the Section's requirement that cooperative
healthcare infrastructure be operational before decriminalization of any given
substance category takes full effect within a network's geographic area.
Congress finds that the implementation challenges experienced in Oregon's
rollout were primarily infrastructure-deployment challenges, not evidence against
the underlying policy, and that this Act's requirement of Guaranteed Provision
Standard delivery -- including accessible cooperative healthcare with walk-in
substance use crisis services -- prior to the activation of Peace Keeper
jurisdiction over substance use emergencies is designed to ensure that the
health-pathway infrastructure is in place before enforcement jurisdiction
transfers.

(b) FEDERAL DECRIMINALIZATION.-- Effective on the date of enactment of this Act:

    (1) the personal use and possession of any controlled substance in a quantity
    consistent with personal use shall not constitute a federal offense, and no
    person shall be prosecuted under any federal statute for conduct consisting
    solely of the personal use or possession of a controlled substance for
    personal use;

    (2) the possession of drug paraphernalia associated with personal use of a
    controlled substance shall not constitute a federal offense; and

    (3) no federal funding shall be provided to any state or local law enforcement
    agency that enforces state or local laws criminalizing the personal use or
    possession of controlled substances in quantities consistent with personal
    use, as a condition of any federal law enforcement grant or cooperative
    agreement; provided, however, that paragraph (3) of this subsection shall
    take effect with respect to any given state or territory on the later of:
    (A) two years after the date of enactment of this Act; or (B) the date on
    which the Secretary of Health and Human Services certifies that certified
    Qualified Federated Network cooperative healthcare capacity within that state
    or territory is sufficient to provide walk-in substance use crisis services
    to not less than forty percent of the state or territory's population;
    nothing in this proviso shall delay the operative effect of paragraphs (1)
    and (2) of this subsection, which are effective nationwide on the date of
    enactment regardless of healthcare infrastructure status.

(c) HEALTH PATHWAY.-- Persons experiencing substance use crises within the
geographic boundaries of a Qualified Federated Network shall be directed to
the cooperative healthcare pathway rather than the justice pathway. Specifically:

    (1) Peace Keepers responding to substance use emergencies under their
    jurisdiction pursuant to Section 301(b)(3) of Title III of this Act shall
    provide immediate overdose reversal assistance, connect the person with
    healthcare cooperative resources, and offer a warm referral to the network's
    substance use treatment services, without any report to law enforcement
    unless the person requests such contact;

    (2) the cooperative healthcare enterprises serving each Qualified Federated
    Network shall maintain walk-in access to substance use crisis services without
    appointment, without insurance requirement, and without disclosure of
    substance use information to any party outside the healthcare relationship
    without the person's explicit consent; and

    (3) the Accountability Coordination DAO shall not receive reports of personal
    substance use as reports of harm to another person, and shall treat substance
    use that affects only the person using as a health matter within the
    healthcare cooperative's jurisdiction rather than an accountability matter
    within the DAO's jurisdiction.

(d) MENTAL HEALTH CRISIS RESPONSE.-- Persons experiencing mental health crises
within Qualified Federated Networks shall receive healthcare-centered responses
on the following terms:

    (1) every Qualified Federated Network shall maintain a Mental Health Crisis
    Response team, distinct from the Peace Keeper program, comprising trained
    mental health practitioners and peer support specialists available on a
    twenty-four-hour basis to respond to mental health crises within the
    network's boundaries without law enforcement involvement;

    (2) the Mental Health Crisis Response team shall have the authority to
    coordinate voluntary short-term crisis stabilization through the
    Transformative Justice Center or cooperative healthcare facility, without
    any requirement of judicial authorization except where the person is
    an immediate danger to the life of another person and all voluntary
    crisis response options have been exhausted; and

    (3) no person shall be involuntarily committed to any psychiatric facility
    on the basis of a crisis response initiated by a Peace Keeper or a Mental
    Health Crisis Response team without a judicial determination of necessity
    made within twenty-four hours of any involuntary hold, with the person
    represented by counsel of their choosing throughout that proceeding.

(e) EXISTING CONVICTIONS.-- All federal convictions for offenses consisting
solely of the personal use or possession of controlled substances in quantities
consistent with personal use shall be vacated automatically upon the date of
enactment of this Act. Persons currently serving federal sentences solely for
such offenses shall be released immediately, with immediate access to Federated
Commons Membership pursuant to Section 103 of Title I of this Act. No petition,
application, or judicial proceeding shall be required for the vacatur and release
provisions of this subsection.

