SEC. 405. FOREIGN POLICY COHERENCE PROVISION.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) FINDING.-- Congress finds that the values of transformative justice,
community sovereignty, material security, and the decentralization of power
that this Act embodies domestically are inconsistent with a foreign policy based
on coercion, regime change, the projection of military power in service of
extractive economic arrangements, and the export of the carceral and surveillance
models this Act is designed to replace. A nation that commits, through this Act
and the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act, to governing
itself through federated commons institutions under principles of self-
determination, restorative accountability, and material security cannot credibly
pursue a foreign policy that denies those same principles to other nations and
peoples.

(b) DIRECTIVE TO THE SECRETARY OF STATE.-- The Secretary of State is hereby
directed to initiate, within one year of the date of enactment of this Act,
a comprehensive review of United States foreign assistance programs, security
cooperation agreements, and multilateral institution participation to assess
the consistency of current American foreign policy with the values established
by this Act and the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act.
The review shall specifically assess:

    (1) whether any United States foreign assistance program funds, supports,
    or provides technical assistance for carceral infrastructure, surveillance
    systems, predictive policing technology, or law enforcement equipment in
    recipient countries;

    (2) whether any United States security cooperation agreement requires or
    incentivizes recipient countries to adopt criminal justice policies
    inconsistent with the transformative justice principles of this Act;

    (3) whether any United States participation in multilateral institutions
    supports structural adjustment conditions, intellectual property regimes,
    or trade rules that prevent recipient nations from developing the commons
    infrastructure that this Act and the Federal Resilience and Decentralization
    Initiatives Act establish domestically; and

    (4) the opportunities for realigning foreign assistance and security
    cooperation toward support for commons institutions, restorative justice
    programs, and community-governed material security infrastructure in
    recipient nations.

(c) REPORT TO CONGRESS.-- The Secretary of State shall submit the findings and
recommendations of the review required by subsection (b) of this Section to
Congress within two years of the date of enactment of this Act. The report
shall identify specific program changes, treaty modifications, and multilateral
institution positions that would align United States foreign policy with the
values established by this Act, and shall serve as the primary policy foundation
for the subsequent legislative vehicle addressing the full scope of United States
defense posture and international engagement, anticipated in the findings of
Section 906(c) of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act.

(d) PROHIBITION ON EXPORT OF CARCERAL TECHNOLOGY.-- Effective on the date of
enactment of this Act, no federal agency shall provide funding, technical
assistance, or equipment to any foreign government for the purpose of:

    (1) constructing, operating, or expanding correctional facilities whose
    design, governance, or operational model is inconsistent with the
    transformative justice principles of this Act;

    (2) deploying Predictive Policing Systems, mass surveillance infrastructure,
    or social credit scoring systems against civilian populations; or

    (3) suppressing community organizing, cooperative enterprise development,
    commons institution formation, or any other activity consistent with the
    values of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act.


================================================================================
TITLE V -- ADMINISTRATIVE AND JUDICIAL PROVISIONS
================================================================================

The purpose of this Title is to establish the administrative framework, judicial
review mechanisms, dependency provisions, conforming amendments, and
appropriations authorities necessary to make the preceding Titles operative and
durable. As with the equivalent provisions of the Federal Resilience and
Decentralization Initiatives Act, this Title does not create new substantive
rights or obligations. It provides the legal infrastructure through which the
rights and obligations established in Titles I through IV are administered,
enforced, and protected.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 501. DEPENDENCY ON THE FRDI ACT.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) STRUCTURAL DEPENDENCY.-- The transformative justice architecture established
by this Act is structurally dependent upon the material security infrastructure
established by the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act.
The Guaranteed Provision Standard -- providing permanent housing, adequate
nutrition, accessible healthcare, connectivity, and knowledge access to every
Commons Member -- is the foundational condition without which the accountability
framework of this Act cannot function as designed. Specifically:

    (1) the voluntary character of the Harm Repair Agreement process established
    in Title II of this Act depends upon the person who caused harm having
    genuine material security that is not contingent on the outcome of any
    accountability proceeding;

    (2) the transformative capacity of the Resilience Campus and Transformative
    Justice Center established in Titles I and IV of this Act depends upon those
    facilities operating within a functioning Qualified Federated Network that
    delivers the Guaranteed Provision Standard to their residents; and

    (3) the community safety architecture of Title III of this Act depends upon
    the material conditions that generate harmful behavior being progressively
    addressed by the commons infrastructure of the Federal Resilience and
    Decentralization Initiatives Act.

(b) TRIGGERING CONDITIONS.-- The following provisions of this Act shall not take
effect in any geographic area until a certified Qualified Federated Network
serving that area has achieved certification pursuant to Title I of the Federal
Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act, or has been granted provisional
certification through the expedited pathway of Section 103(e) of that Act:

    (1) the Resilience Campus conversion provisions of Section 102 of Title I
    of this Act, to the extent they require the receiving Qualified Federated
    Cooperative to deliver the Guaranteed Provision Standard to campus residents;

    (2) the immediate Federated Commons Membership entitlement of Section 103
    of Title I of this Act, to the extent it requires the receiving Qualified
    Federated Network to deliver the Guaranteed Provision Standard; and

    (3) the Peace Keeper program requirements of Section 301 of Title III of
    this Act, to the extent they require operational integration with the
    network's Accountability Coordination DAO.

(c) FEDERAL BACKSTOP.-- Where a certified Qualified Federated Network does not
yet exist to serve a community affected by the decommissioning provisions of
Section 101 of Title I of this Act, the federal government shall:

    (1) provide the Guaranteed Provision Standard directly to any person released
    from federal correctional custody in that area, through the mechanisms of
    existing federal housing, nutrition, and healthcare programs, until a
    certified Qualified Federated Network is established; and

    (2) accelerate the Bootstrap Grant and coverage extension provisions of
    Sections 105 and 106 of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization
    Initiatives Act for that area, treating the absence of a receiving network
    as a coverage gap of the highest priority.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 502. CONSTITUTIONAL SAFE HARBOR.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Any federal officer, employee, or agent who in good faith takes any action to
implement the provisions of this Act -- including actions that result in the
release of persons from federal correctional custody, the conversion of
correctional facilities to Resilience Campuses, the vacatur of monetary
assessments, or the transfer of community safety functions to Qualified Federated
Networks -- shall not be subject to civil or criminal liability under any federal
or state law arising solely from the performance of those implementation duties,
on terms equivalent to the Constitutional Safe Harbor established under Section
1101 of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 503. SEVERABILITY.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

If any provision of this Act, or the application of any provision to any person
or circumstance, is held invalid by a court of competent jurisdiction, the
remainder of this Act and the application of its provisions to other persons or
circumstances shall not be affected. Each Title of this Act is independently
operative and shall remain in full force and effect if any other Title or any
provision thereof is held invalid. The transformative justice architecture
established by this Act is designed with sufficient redundancy that the
invalidation of any specific mechanism does not eliminate the architecture's
capacity to function through alternative pathways.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 504. CONFORMING AMENDMENTS.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) RESTORATIVE TERMINOLOGY -- DESIGNATED FEDERAL STATUTES.-- The following
specific substitutions are hereby made in the designated federal statutes, to
align the terminology of those statutes with the restorative framework of this
Act as applied to persons subject to proceedings under this Act:

    (1) In 18 U.S.C. Chapter 229 (Postsentence Administration) and Chapter 232
    (Miscellaneous Sentencing Provisions), the term "offender" shall be replaced
    by "person subject to a Harm Repair Agreement" wherever it appears in
    provisions applicable to persons who have entered a Harm Repair Agreement
    pursuant to Title II of this Act.

    (2) In 18 U.S.C. sections 3621 through 3632 (Bureau of Prisons provisions),
    the terms "inmate" and "prisoner" shall be replaced by "person in federal
    custody" wherever those terms appear in provisions applicable to persons
    held in facilities subject to the decommissioning schedule of Section 101
    of Title I of this Act, effective on the decommissioning date of each
    facility.

    (3) In 34 U.S.C. Chapter 303 (Prisoner Rights), the term "prisoner" shall
    be replaced by "person in federal custody" wherever it appears in provisions
    applicable to persons held in federal facilities.

    (4) Nothing in this subsection shall be construed to amend the terminology
    of any federal statute with respect to persons not subject to proceedings
    under this Act, or to affect the meaning of any term in any statute for
    purposes of determining eligibility, liability, or rights under any program
    not established by this Act.

(b) TITLE 18 -- CRIMES AND CRIMINAL PROCEDURE.-- Title 18 of the United States
Code is hereby amended to:

    (1) remove all mandatory minimum sentences for offenses whose controlling
    conduct does not involve the use or threatened use of physical force against
    a person, effective for all sentences imposed after the date of enactment
    and retroactively applicable through the Second Look Mandate of Section 104
    of Title I of this Act;

    (2) provide that any sentence of incarceration imposed for an offense whose
    controlling conduct consists solely of personal use or possession of a
    controlled substance is hereby vacated pursuant to Section 404(e) of Title
    IV of this Act; and

    (3) incorporate the Harm Repair Agreement as a formal sentencing alternative
    available in any federal criminal proceeding, with the court treating the
    voluntary entry into and good-faith progress under a Harm Repair Agreement
    as a basis for imposing a non-custodial sentence or for deferring sentence
    pending completion of the agreement.

(c) SENTENCING REFORM ACT OF 1984.-- The Sentencing Reform Act of 1984, codified
at 18 U.S.C. sections 3551 et seq., is hereby amended to:

    (1) require federal sentencing courts to consider the availability of the
    Harm Repair Agreement pathway as an alternative to incarceration in every
    case in which the defendant has entered or expressed willingness to enter
    such an agreement;

    (2) direct the United States Sentencing Commission to promulgate guidelines
    treating the completion of a Harm Repair Agreement as a significant
    mitigating factor in sentencing, with a presumption in favor of non-custodial
    sentences for defendants who have made good-faith progress under such an
    agreement; and

    (3) incorporate the developmental findings of Section 403(a) of Title IV of
    this Act into the sentencing guidelines applicable to persons under the age
    of twenty-five, creating a presumption in favor of the commons accountability
    pathway for all such persons.

(d) COMPREHENSIVE CRIME CONTROL ACT AND ASSET FORFEITURE.-- All provisions of
federal law authorizing civil asset forfeiture against persons who have not been
convicted of a criminal offense are hereby amended to eliminate such
authorization, consistent with Section 201(a)(3) of Title II of this Act.
Federal criminal asset forfeiture shall be available only upon conviction,
only with respect to property directly traceable to the convicted offense,
and only after a judicial finding that the forfeiture is proportionate to the
offense.

(e) THE 1033 PROGRAM REPEAL.-- Section 1033 of the National Defense
Authorization Act for Fiscal Year 1997 is repealed as provided in Section 306
of Title III of this Act.

(f) CONTROLLED SUBSTANCES ACT.-- The Controlled Substances Act, codified at
21 U.S.C. section 801 et seq., is hereby amended to:

    (1) remove personal use and possession of any controlled substance in
    quantities consistent with personal use from the schedules of prohibited
    conduct, consistent with the federal decriminalization established in
    Section 404(b) of Title IV of this Act; and

    (2) direct the Drug Enforcement Administration to promulgate revised
    quantity thresholds for each scheduled substance distinguishing between
    quantities consistent with personal use, which shall not be subject to
    federal enforcement, and quantities consistent with distribution, which
    shall remain subject to federal enforcement.

(g) JUVENILE JUSTICE AND DELINQUENCY PREVENTION ACT.-- The Juvenile Justice and
Delinquency Prevention Act of 1974, codified at 34 U.S.C. section 11101 et seq.,
is hereby amended to:

    (1) prohibit the placement of any person under the age of eighteen in any
    adult correctional facility under any circumstances, consistent with Section
    403(e) of Title IV of this Act;

    (2) require that all federal juvenile justice programming be consistent with
    the transformative justice principles of this Act; and

    (3) direct the Office of Juvenile Justice and Delinquency Prevention to
    incorporate the Accountability Pod framework and Harm Repair Agreement
    process of Title II of this Act into the standards and guidelines it
    provides to state and local juvenile justice systems.

