SEC. 505. AUTHORIZATION OF APPROPRIATIONS.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) GENERAL AUTHORIZATION.-- There are authorized to be appropriated to carry
out the purposes of this Act such sums as may be necessary for each fiscal year
following the date of enactment, subject to the specific authorizations and
funding mechanisms established in this Section.

(b) RESENTENCING REVIEW COMMISSION.-- There are authorized to be appropriated
to the Federal Resentencing Review Commission established under Section 104(b)
of Title I of this Act:

    (1) not less than fifty million dollars for the first fiscal year following
    enactment, for establishment and initial review operations; and

    (2) not less than thirty million dollars for each subsequent fiscal year,
    for ongoing review and the exercise of continuing jurisdiction pursuant to
    Section 104(d) of Title I of this Act.

(c) RESILIENCE CAMPUS CONVERSION.-- There are authorized to be appropriated
for the conversion of federal correctional facilities to Resilience Campuses
pursuant to Section 102 of Title I of this Act:

    (1) not less than two billion dollars for the first fiscal year following
    enactment, for the assessment, environmental remediation, and initial
    physical conversion of Tier 1 facilities; and

    (2) such sums as may be necessary for subsequent fiscal years, with the
    total appropriation reflecting the decommissioning schedule of Section 101
    of Title I of this Act and the expectation that correctional spending
    reductions will progressively fund the conversion program through the
    reinvestment mechanism of Section 305(b) of Title III of this Act.

(d) REPARATIVE JUSTICE COMMISSION.-- There are authorized to be appropriated
to the Reparative Justice Commission established under Section 202 of Title II
of this Act:

    (1) not less than one hundred million dollars for the first fiscal year
    following enactment, for establishment, community hearing processes, and
    initial historical assessment work; and

    (2) not less than fifty million dollars for each subsequent fiscal year
    through the Commission's completion of its initial comprehensive report,
    and such sums as may be necessary for ongoing operations thereafter.

(e) COMMUNITY SAFETY INFRASTRUCTURE.-- There are authorized to be appropriated
for the community safety infrastructure investment established under Section 305
of Title III of this Act, supplementing the correctional savings reinvestment
mechanism, not less than five hundred million dollars for each of the first five
fiscal years following enactment, with priority allocation to communities
designated as Priority Underserved Areas under the Federal Resilience and
Decentralization Initiatives Act and to communities with the highest historical
rates of federal incarceration.

(f) TRANSFORMATIVE JUSTICE CENTERS.-- There are authorized to be appropriated
for the establishment of Transformative Justice Centers pursuant to Section 401
of Title IV of this Act, through the Bootstrap Grant Program of the Federal
Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act with dedicated allocation for
this purpose, not less than two hundred fifty million dollars for each of the
first five fiscal years following enactment.

(g) FUNDING PRINCIPLES.-- The appropriations authorized by this Section shall
be understood as front-loaded transition investments: the long-term fiscal
trajectory of this Act is toward reduced public expenditure on justice
infrastructure, as the material security of the commons reduces the frequency
of harmful behavior and as the commons economy's own productive capacity
progressively finances the institutions this Act establishes. The Congressional
Budget Office is directed, in scoring the fiscal impact of this Act, to account
for the reduction in federal correctional expenditure, the reduction in the
social costs of incarceration on communities and families, and the productive
economic contribution of persons whose participation in the commons economy is
enabled by the Federated Commons Membership entitlements of Section 103 of
Title I of this Act.

